&lt;p&gt;cach=e_ninjA ;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;e-Mail me if Found&lt;br&gt;
cache_ninja@hotmail.com&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364722161"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="673028">llenseuqm</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This was our principal target for the day. It took us about 45 minutes from the parking lot to get here. Lots of places to look but with the help of prior logs we quickly found the ammo can. Thanks for keeping this oldie alive! TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362108089"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5454530">MajorDad</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This was my cache of the day! Purposely built a road trip to find it today. Lovely pond and trail system. It definitely got the heart pumping. Since I landed 5.5hrs late, I didn't make it to parking until about 1900/7pm (about an hour before dusk/parking closing). Had to scramble there and back so I couldn't do any more caches along the way - sad part. At GZ, I made the find quickly but ONLY because of a previous finders' log hint. The cache was 61’ off per my iPhone. Highly recommend reading logs. Thanks for keeping this old one up and active and TFTC!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361826570"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-17T15:50:37</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54140630">EnderLemming</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Oh my goodness! What a hike and what a cache! Coordinates were off by about 60ft and this was also my first ammo can find. Many spider webs along the way. When we got to ground zero, I was worried about that I couldn't find it. I wasn't about to hike 1.5 miles for nothing and eventually saw something and made the find!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361873741"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="444536">charliewhiskey</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I regret to say these TB's aren't in the cache:

The 13th Spider Geocoin
Bee Happy</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361873626"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="444536">charliewhiskey</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">mr. charliewhiskey and I came out from Oregon to visit for a few days on our way to visit family and attend a West Point Military Academy 50th class reunion.  We had a couple hours to kill before we could check into our hotel.  What to do, what to do.  It seemed silly to be so close to New Jersey's oldest and not try for it.  So despite the heat and my thrice-repaired knees, we set out to try.  It was slow going for us, but thanks to a good hint from a previous finder, once we neared GZ we spied the cache right off.

So for future seekers, here's the hint: As you near GZ, you will see two long rows of rocks that parallel the trail.  Go to the left end of the row further from the trail and peer over the edge.  You should be able to see the ammo can tucked into a cavity in the lower rocks.

Thanks for keeping this grand, old cache going. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="35.335583" lon="-106.474433"><time>2001-01-15T00:00:00</time><name>GC190</name><desc>Open Space 6 by Adopted by Team Tuxawuxa</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC190</url><urlname>Open Space 6</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Letterbox Hybrid</type><groundspeak:cache id="400" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Open Space 6</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Adopted by Team Tuxawuxa</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="71315">Team Tuxawuxa</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Letterbox Hybrid</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="37" inc="1">Horses</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>New Mexico</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="red"&gt;NEW MEXICO's OLDEST GEOCACHE&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now in a NEW LOCATION NEAR YOU !!! Its under a Juniper tree, so its easy to find. A Lock'n'lock box with a copy of all the logs posted during the last 12 years and other goodies.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;div align="center"&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://nmgeocaching.com" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="http://i481.photobucket.com/albums/rr176/tuxawuxa/GCNM.jpg" vspace="10" hspace="10" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Fresh log-book.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Can be accessed from N 35 20.232, W 106 29.175.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="820208966"><groundspeak:date>2018-12-17T23:07:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="531429">Heartland Cacher</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache has been locked to prevent ongoing discussion that belongs in the forums.

Thanks

Heartland Cacher
Your friendly Volunteer Cache Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="818834638"><groundspeak:date>2018-12-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="78712">rragan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I had a watch on this one and was dismayed to see the archival.  I read the log history to get an understanding of your  ire and was confused, as the replacement seemed anything but an unscrupulous throw down. I see the individual has clarified and added more details on the efforts he went through before choosing to improve the container. As the owner, you are correct that no one should do a replacement without your permission. It is your property. Still it seemed like a good deal of effort was made to contact you and get approval and the replacement was made with respect for New Mexico and the historical significance of this being the oldest in NM and the oldest Letterbox. 

I am booked on the GeoGearheads podcast on December 27 to discuss preserving our heirloom/heritage caches so the loss of one of these is a loss to everyone and made my topic that much more meaningful to me. I urge you to consider unarchiving this one and taking whatever action you prefer with respect to the container. Thanks for keeping your other old ones going. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="818750825"><groundspeak:date>2018-12-04T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="14565665">TreasureGoddess16</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">OMG I see my Huey TB has been dropped in this now archived cache!!  Will the CO please go and retrieve him (and the other TB in there) and move him along to another premium cache.   If you are unarchiving (is that such a thing?) this cache, then he can stay there for someone else to come and grab and move along. I just don’t want him sitting there in an archived cache! Huey needs to be on the move.... TY!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="818748737"><groundspeak:date>2018-12-04T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="90907">SerenityNow</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Well this is sure a fine mess! We are from North Royalton, Ohio and decided to take a road trip out west and find some interesting caches along with old ones. We refreshed our pq a few days ago and this cache was still active. We hiked out to it and found the nice yellow ammo box that we see in the photos section for this cache chained to the tree at the coordinates. We signed the log and left two travel bugs, one that originated in New York and one from Belgium. Now that we are back in our hotel room far from the area, logging our finds, we see that this cache was archived yesterday! We feel terrible that we dropped them into a cache that no one may visit again. We would really appreciate it if someone from the area would go out and retrieve the bugs. 

Thanks for your understanding in this matter,
Tom &amp; Anna Mary

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="818609954"><groundspeak:date>2018-12-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="11220918">The6thHobbit</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">You 11:31 AM

My apologies Team Tuxawuxa, I tried to contact you back in December 2017 about the condition of Open Space 6 (see below). It was a destroyed Tupperware, and I just wanted to help. When I didn't hear from you, I logged everything on the site as I went trying to get communication from you. I didn't want anything to be a surprise or disrespectful. I have never seen any response from you on this site, until yesterday's response to hottbloon, so I even wondered if you had left the hobby. The weekend I replaced this cache I even spoke with the owner of Open Space 7 (sdjd222) at a geocaching event in Albuquerque, trying to get information on contacting you, but also asking thoughts about replacing the damaged container. She thought the replacement would be OK. 

I love New Mexico, and I love geocaching, and I really wanted to put a seriously honoring geocache at Open Space 6... and I feel people have really enjoyed the New Mexico themed ammo can. I'm very sorry, I was trying hard to be anything but unscrupulous this whole time. I hope my previous logs on the cache show that...

If you would like to re-activate this cache, I can work out a weekend time when I come into town and pull the container I have placed there. I would rather see my container gone, and see the oldest cache in New Mexico/oldest letterbox in the world re-enabled.

Humbly,

James (The6thHobbit)


You Dec 6, 2017 12:16 PM

Hey Guys,

 My name is James Hastings (geocaching name: The6thHobbit). I'm originally from the Albuquerque area, but discovered geocaching after I moved to Oklahoma. I'll be coming back to visit with friends December 13-17, and I'm currently hooked on Finding the oldest cache in each state. So, I'll be going after Open Space Letterbox 7 and Open Space 6 on this visit.
 I note, per some of the most recent logs on OS6, a new container may be needed there. I have several extra ammo cans of various sizes, and I'd be happy to replace the old container with one of these if it's OK with you. I can pick anything up from you for the cache beforehand, or drop anything off to you afterward, if you'd like too.

Blessings,

James
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="42.668133" lon="-77.334767"><time>2000-05-26T00:00:00</time><name>GC39</name><desc>The Spot by GPS_Fool</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC39</url><urlname>The Spot</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="57" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>The Spot</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>GPS_Fool</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="306">gpsfool</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>New York</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;Update May 28, 2023 - I visited the cache today, 23 years and 2 days since I originally placed this cache - Who would have guessed it would still be going strong after all these years? I hear it&amp;#39;s like the 6th oldest cache still running? As for myself - 23 years older, a bit heavier, and WAY more out of shape.... My last visit was 3-4 years ago. My goal for today was to put back in place the ammo box container originally used for this cache. During my last visit 3-4 years ago I swapped-in a temporary box, allowing me to take the ammo box home for needed maintenance - the hinge had broken such that the box no longer sealed. This original box is back in place as of today - 5/28/23, with a fixed hinge and new coat of paint. I also added a new logbook for signing. The substitute box, a plastic box with snap-tight lid was small enough so I just placed it into the ammo box. Other observations.... Lots of trail erosion since I placed this cache 23 years ago, many herd paths too. Seems to me too that the hills have got steeper? A few Notes: &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A:  The ammo box was not the box used when I created this cache in 2000. I used a 5-gal bucket with a gamma-seal lid. Well - that did not work out too well - at times it was almost impossible to unscrew that lid, also, it would freeze shut and finally someone did not tighten that lid enough, allowing the bucket to fill with water (oops). Exact timing on when I substituted in the ammo can has been lost to time - perhaps looking back through the logs one might figure it out?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B: I have the original log books, stored safely in a fireproof safe. They&amp;#39;re mostly still readable, however in rough shape from water damage.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Update 3/31/2025 - a rundown of the history of &amp;quot;The Spot&amp;quot; as I see it&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logbook&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have the original three logbooks.  I took the first two from the cache for safe keeping on or about 8/26/17.  they were all wet and in bad shape. For the original logbook there are some pages missing at the beginning of the log, first post is dates 4/22/01. First post logged on Geocaching.com is dated 4/13/21.  Given the newness of the activity back then, the remoteness and harsh winters in the area, spring 2001 dates are probably the first finds. The youngest date I can find in the original logbook is from 7/6/11.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The second log book (in worse shape than the first), first date is 8/20/11 - I see the first entry - from me. last entry I can find is 4/1/17. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I also have the third logbook, I did not place this one - I assume a fellow geocached did as the original two were filled and in bad shape.  Log dates starting 8/27/16.  The last entry in this second logbook is dated 8/8/20. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The cache box&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The original cache box was a 5gal bucket with a gamma-seal lid. that did not last too long, it was hard to open/close and along the way someone did not seal it, the bucket filled with water. it was removed from the cache site on 12/26/01 by a friendly geocacher whoi showed up to log the cache. The cache was returned to me.  I replaced the cache on 4/27/02 with an ammo can, painted camo green.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Down the road, reading the log entries (they are emailed to me) it became clear the ammo box was in dire need of replacement or fix up. I am assuming it was shortly after the 8/8/20 entry in the third logbook I visited the cache, took the Ammo box and the three logbooks.  I do not remember what the interum cachebox was.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It took a while, but I fixed up the ammo box, new hinges and fresh paint job and returned it to the cache - that was in May 2023 and so far, it&amp;#39;s holding up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;#39;s a delight the cache is still going strong - I have two observations....   A:  Now being 24 years older it&amp;#39;s a heck of a lot harder for me to get to the spot. B: Incredible trail erosion from when I placed the cache.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Have fun, stay safe&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;GPSfool. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Original posting:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have placed one in the Finger Lakes region of Western New York State. It&amp;#39;s located on public land.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Where: Datum WGS84 N 42 Degrees 40.088&amp;#39; W 77 Degrees 20.086&amp;#39;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;UTM Coordinates: 18T 0308671 UTM 4726605&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Stash: A .50 Cal Ammo box containing a log book, and a variety of &amp;quot;prizes&amp;quot; for those who find the stash.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All contents are enclosed in individual zip lock baggies, and the log book requests that all who take a prize also place something of interest in the stash. Additionally, in the log book this web site URL is listed as well as my e-mail address. Visitors are encouraged to leave a message in the log book and take a picture of themselves (Leave the camera in the stash)!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The stash has been mostly concealed w/ rocks, leaves, sticks, etc...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I suppose bushwacking to this stash may be possible however I caution the terrain is VERY rugged, hilly, etc... If you choose the best approach no dangerous terrain navigation is necessary&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Disclaimer: You are under no obligation to hunt my cache. You do so at your own risk. Like any outdoor sport, it carries the risk of unforeseen hazards. Use your best judgment with the environment and conditions. As conditions and cache locations may vary, it is the responsibility of the searcher to be familiar with the conditions in the area to be searched, to adequately prepare for those conditions, and to conduct oneself safely and responsibly and remain within his or her personal abilities and limitations. Children should be well supervised. When and if you find a cache, you are under no obligation to touch it, reach it, climb to it, dig for it, pick it up, or even open it. Open it at your own risk. If food or drink is present, do not consume it, throw it out. Individual Geostash and GPS cache sponsors assume no liability for events, which may occur, related directly or indirectly to your searching for a stash.&lt;/p&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364956941"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T07:44:04</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42951374">dlinst84</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#10000

All right, I was saving this one for 10,000 and this was an adventure. The Adventure Lab in the area misled me where to park and I end up making this extremely harder hike than what it should be. I read logs later I could park somewhere else and walk down versus the other way. Oh well, I need the exercise. This was definitely an adventure. I found it about 30 feet away from the coordinates I had a little more down the hill. I saw something I was like well let’s go, but I didn’t want to go down, but I did anyway.

Thank you for the oldie, keeping us alive and for the adventure on a Tuesday cooler morning</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364635389"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T11:24:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1963574">Ms.Blonde</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Out and about today with this as a target. Finally off my bucket list! Tftc! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364604920"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T09:50:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3711188">barbh32</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">5757 days of geocaching and today is the day i finally came to the spot!!  Took us a bit at the end but we got it!  Now to make our way out </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364422981"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T14:09:11</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="46758867">ravenbcm</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Legendary find!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364256211"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T19:03:50</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3818176">buckeye1725</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC. Out here in the hills of New York, tucked into the Finger Lakes region, this Florida flatlander quickly learned that “a nice walk to a cache” means something a little different up here than it does back home. Down in Florida, we measure elevation change by speed bumps, bridge approaches, and maybe the occasional sandy rise if we are feeling adventurous. Up here, the land has a way of reminding you that gravity is still very much in charge.

The trip out started off with that wonderful mix of anticipation and curiosity that makes geocaching such a great excuse to explore places I might otherwise never have found. The views along the way were outstanding, and I took a few moments to just enjoy being somewhere completely different from my usual caching grounds. The Finger Lakes hills really do offer some beautiful scenery, and this cache gave me a good reason to slow down and take it all in.

Of course, the “going out” part had me thinking this was not too bad. Great view, fresh air, interesting terrain, and another smiley waiting somewhere ahead. Then came the reminder that what goes down must come back up. By the time I was working my way back, I felt like I had just finished leg day at the gym. My Florida legs were definitely questioning some of my life choices, but that is part of the fun. A cache that makes you earn it usually makes the find that much better.

Made the find, signed the log as Buckeye 1725, and enjoyed the satisfaction of another cache found in a beautiful part of the country. I also left several path tags behind for those who wander after me. Hopefully they bring a smile to the next cachers who make the trek.

Thanks for placing and maintaining this cache. It was a great Finger Lakes adventure, a good workout, and a memorable stop for this flatlander from Florida.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="698796620"><groundspeak:date>2017-06-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Third times the charm.   The spot has been on my list for a while!  This was the third time I could have made the attempt... And the first time I actually made it to ground zero. 

This is a sturdy foot wear cache for sure. 

Really glad I made it here at long last, but while packing for my trip, I found the haunted gate in a rarely used suitcase.  I didn't fulfill the gates primary mission but dropped it in this high value cache so good Geocacher cash pick it up. 

Thanks for the awesome and elderly cause.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="35.16275" lon="-80.7356"><time>2000-09-30T00:00:00</time><name>GC70</name><desc>Octopus Garden by AdventureTom</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC70</url><urlname>Octopus Garden</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Unknown Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="112" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Octopus Garden</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>AdventureTom</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="11154">adventuretom</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Unknown Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>North Carolina</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;strong&gt;NOTE: If you send me a question, please include your email with the request, otherwise it will take me a while to reply. If you do not send your email, I may not reply at all. Just a heads up.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;North Carolina's Oldest Geocache - Dedicated to my Dad - Top Cat.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Adventuretom is happy to announce that Octopus Garden is now the 37th oldest active Geocache in the world (out of 3,150,000+)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note: the concept of a moving geocache no longer exists. Please do not move the cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is an "Easy" hunt.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You can solve the puzzle at the first point or with your brain power.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;PARK AT THE TRAIL HEAD on Margaret Wallace Road across the street from Fire Station 29.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="red"&gt;If you cross the bridge you are doing it wrong. Don't go over the bridge. NOTE: There is NO creek crossing as part of this cache. If you end up on the wrong side of the creek you've done it wrong. Go back and read the part where it says don't cross the bridge. Crossing the creek will make the cache more vulnerable to muggles. Don't do it.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What is the missing word in this list? Paper Ink Coin Knee Ball Egg Lagoon Latitude?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The possible answers:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1) Pen&lt;br /&gt;
2) Compass&lt;br /&gt;
3) Quarter&lt;br /&gt;
4) Lipstick&lt;br /&gt;
5) Computer&lt;br /&gt;
6) Hair&lt;br /&gt;
7) Bell&lt;br /&gt;
8) Possible&lt;br /&gt;
9) Microphone&lt;br /&gt;
10) Stage&lt;br /&gt;
11) Kiss&lt;br /&gt;
12) Apple&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Go To - N 35 09.672 W 080&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1) 44.499 2)44.149 3) 44.342 4) 44.131 5) 44.100 6) 43.999 7) 44.090 8) 43.199 9) 44.302 10) 43.149 11) 44.200 12) 44.241&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Don't go over the bridge. The answer to the puzzle is at entrance to the bridge you shouldn't cross.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364737720"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53184652">Eloise6718</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Mygranddad, beemerdon, bought me a premium membership and brought me down here for my 100th find. Thanks, and another favorite point.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363585962"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T15:18:06</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="30920028">mathmanbill</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">OCW JoeBum on day 3 of 4 of our caching roadtrip based around ATL. After trudging through the jungle to get Modoc last evening, we opted to stay in Aiken afterwards and picked up a few caches here before heading up to Charlotte and then Clemson. 

Our 4th state oldie on this trip. Definitely way easier than the adventure we had in getting Modoc yesterday so we were much appreciative of this one!  TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363548052"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T13:20:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3588517">JoeBum</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 3 of an oldie trip with mathmanbill. This was our main target for today and our 4th state oldest. Lots of water running in the nearby creek and a wet approach, but cache is all good. I think that rope has been there for a bit. Thanks for keeping the oldest in NC and mystery running!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363638709"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5268266">Pine Baron</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">5525. Heading to NJ from GA with Piglet404 and had this as the main target on my list. Parked at the trailhead lot and made our way down the path to GZ. A downed tree almost thwarted us, but eventually, Piglet made the grab. Signed the log and traded some. Thanx for keeping this great old one going!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363490596"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T10:23:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25100005">suusinhawaii</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">While in Charlotte for an expo this weekend my husband and I really wanted to get NC's oldest before heading home. It is only about 10 min from our hotel. We were lucky that it was Memorial day and traffic was almost non existent. 
I prepped beforehand by checking out the puzzle and reached out to a geo friend to double check I had the right coords.  I found a flas tag! We signed/stamped the log. Thank you for keeping this oldie going.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="46.808617" lon="-100.726833"><time>2001-03-25T00:00:00</time><name>GC551</name><desc>The Buck Stops Here! by Dakota</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC551</url><urlname>The Buck Stops Here!</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1361" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>The Buck Stops Here!</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Dakota</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="5783">dakota</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>North Dakota</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>The cache is within 80 paces of an easily accessable road. Park carefully.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This is the oldest cache in North Dakota. It's original location was about 200 meters east. It was repositioned after the fence was built to solve accessabilty problems. The cache is a clear plastic container with a blue lid. Access is usually easy, but may be more difficult (wet and sloppy) after heavy rain/snow.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Rock around the clock!</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364892326"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10744332">WanderTrek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from Temecula, California! This is part of our three-week, 11-state road trip now  heading home through 7 more states from GeoWoodstock XXII in Hutchinson, Kansas then on to: Nebraska, South Dakota and now North Dakota. Your cache was a must-stop on our itinerary. Thank you for being a part of our journey and for the fun find in a new-to-us state!
Favorite Point for this oldie. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364378674"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T10:11:33</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="887579">dukemartin</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it with Paintedwarrior.  Thanks for the cache. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364371983"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T09:47:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1454863">Paintedwarrior</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Coming from Yellowstone and heading to Gilby. Thanks for this oldie. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364268657"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="598646">tdb1977</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">When I set the trip up to go to Yellowstone for my wife and mine 25th Anniversary, we were going to come via the northern route of North Dakota.  Seeing how this cache was pretty much right off of 94, it became an instance must have for me.  Today, was the day that I would stop off and pick up North Dakota's oldest cache!  Pulled off to the side of the road and made my way back to ground zero, watching where I stepped to not get any unpleasant surprises, I quickly spied the container.  Walked over and retrieved it.  This is my 24th or 25th state oldest cache that I find!  I thumb through the log book quickly and scribble my name on the next line.  Thanks so much for keeping the state's oldest cache going!  All is well here.  Picked up a couple travel bugs while also dropping off a travel bug, whose goal was to get placed into North Dakota's oldest cache!  Mission Complete!  Signed the log and placed back where it was found.  Back onto the highway and continuing to go west!

TDB1977</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362747768"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47911">medicineman</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found in the rain so took to my hatchback briefly to open where it was protected. Favorite for sure. I'm on a road trip to/from Seattle and targeting oldest in each State I pass through. Signed the log, traded path tags and TB's. Thanks</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.569317" lon="-83.86355"><time>2001-01-23T00:00:00</time><name>GC2DBE</name><desc>Ancient Lake by Chuck Fackleman, Mark Robinette</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC2DBE</url><urlname>Ancient Lake</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="11710" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Ancient Lake</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Chuck Fackleman, Mark Robinette</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="32747">swampy ranger</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="0">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="0">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="59" inc="0">Food nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="0">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="37" inc="1">Horses</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Ohio</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>IMPORTANT NOTE !!! DO NOT BUSHWACK ENVIRONMENTALLY SENSITIVE AREA .......DO NOT BUSHWACK ....level easy access, watch for horses and indigenous insects. bug spray use is advised during early spring to late fall. This is a FRAGILE SENSITIVE Ecosystem.. ........DO NOT BRUSHWACK..... Stay on trails.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>06/14/03 inspected and put cache in a green ammo box. No special items. notepad and pencil.Due to high moisture liberally apply bug juice. the winged vampires are fierce. Please use trails on way to cache do not go "overland", this is an easy walk using the trails. Access is from Girdham Road at fire trail, about 1/4 mi North from Ranger compound near corner of Monclova and Girdham, Fire Trail merges with Horse trail. Follow Horse trail it heads first south then west along Swan Creek then swings north to Geocache. please stay on trail till you are at Geocache.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364219103"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T14:06:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="468159">cjhanson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">My 2nd time visiting this cache, Ohio’s oldest. On a road trip with Grandmabonnie and she needed to find it. Pleasant walk to GZ despite a few mosquitoes.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364221954"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="16271950">grandmabonnie44</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A great day to take the walk out to this one. Thanks for keeping this oldie alive. Mosquitoes weren't t6awful TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363884147"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="723797">childofatom</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It is once again time for my bi-annual drive between Utah and New York. I’m always on the lookout for Challenges, caches that fulfill various goals I am working on and just plain interesting caches, or maybe just a reason to stop a mi tie and stretch. This one fit one those criteria! It makes for a roundabout route for sure, but that’s caching. Thanks for adding to my adventure. 

I logged the OTHER oldest Ohio cache way back in 2019 on my very first of these cross country drives. At the time I was unaware of the "controversy" surrounding these caches, so I thought I had crossed Ohio off the list, until I saw a different list... oh well! This was a lovely walk in the woods, passed a half dozen people on horseback along the way who all seemed surprised to find anyone else out there. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363309945"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T15:28:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="19483995">Aegir101</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Aegir101 and beJs are on a 5 day trip from Maryland💪🦀 to MI, IN, KY and OH to complete their second Jasmer loop. Today was day 5 the drive from OH to MI. It was an overcast day but we had fun. We started at an event in Dayton and headed to Columbus then Toledo and Detroit. We stopped along the way to look for old caches, webcams, challenges, and counties, as well as all cache types to stay well rounded. Thanks to all these COs for placing and maintaining these caches. 

This was our last cache in Ohio. Sadly because Delta cancelled our flight last Wednesday we had to go back to Michigan and cut a bunch of Ohio caching short. This was a nice and easy hike albeit buggy. We wanted to park closer but there was no shoulder so we parked near the park maintenance lot and hiked 2.6 miles round trip. We came back on the road which made it about 0.2 shorter on return. Super happy to find this, my 29th state’s oldest cache. AIO, TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363332354"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2938303">bejs</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Aegir101 and bejs from the D.C. area have teamed up for a five day caching tear through Michigan, Indiana, Kentucky, and Ohio, getting the oldests, CAAs, cache types, and finishing our second Jasmer loops.  We are on our last day, mainly in Ohio and wrapping up back in Michigan.

Our last oldie of the trip, and our last cache in Ohio. This was a nice walk from parking in the ranger maintenance yard.  There is a more direct trail from the road, but not really any parking for it.

Thanks for the fun hide, beJs

---
Find # 4564
As found: Traditional Cache 1.5/1.5 Regular</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="36.15705" lon="-96.25225"><time>2001-02-11T00:00:00</time><name>GC272</name><desc>Where Eagles Roost by Craig Wirtz...Adopted by CCATBQFM</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC272</url><urlname>Where Eagles Roost</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="626" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Where Eagles Roost</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Craig Wirtz...Adopted by CCATBQFM</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="109563">captain.crash</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="0">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="17" inc="1">Poisonous plants</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Oklahoma</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Near Keystone Lake Dam. Park on NW side of dam and start following trail around lake.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Container is now a painted large plastic jar. Please take care to rehide the cache well after you have found it.
&lt;p&gt;The area can become very leaf covered as the seasons change. There appears to be a good chance for the usual critters in the warmer months: snakes, ticks, mosquitos.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Original contents of the original 12 x 12 tupperware: Music CD, Computer Game CD, Flashlight (no batteries), Paperback Book, Guest Book w/ Waterproof Camera, SuperBall, &amp;amp; drink Koozie.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;During November to March, on the "river" side of the dam, Bald Eagles roost for the winter. Early in the morning it's great to watch them feed on fish. So after the short trek to the cache, drive over to the NE side of the dam and look across the river for Bald Eagles. Jan 2001, I spotted approximately 12 Eagles.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Have fun!&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>inside of tree; natural cover</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363813095"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T15:53:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3726526">MI Barrel Makers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great hike was fun to get the oldest in the state almost missed us. One of my radar had the challenge in the area but happen to see someone referred to GC 262. I looked up and realized I wanted to be here anyway it’s definitely objective or key objective of the hike today. Other than being a little hot and humid. It did not disappoint. Catches in great shape signed in behind the phone yesterday. Thanks for keeping this oldie alive favorite point for sure.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363634646"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T16:21:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="205965">Moose Mob</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Proud member of the coordinate verification and pencil distribution team.

Roadtrip from Hutchinson to Tulsa.  Grabbing ALs and geocaches along the way.  Watering coronavirus bushes and irritating the ticks!

