</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363560602"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:59:33</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1906272">mdsearcher</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A  bit of a hike to get to this one. Found it. TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364239717"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42481597">cachefinder24315</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A hot day to go out, and lots of trails in the area to get confused on, it was still a fairly short trek out to find this one. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363626514"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="561607">wademercer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Geowoodstock weekend caching with thisiszeppo. Visiting from Dallas Texas. Visiting Kansas to enjoy the event, grab some Kansas counties, and enjoy the Geowoodstock experience. Monday. Time to start the journey back to Dallas. The plan is to grab counties and eventually make our way back home.

Just had to make this stop. Parked and started walking. Went right and followed this arrow for the trail. If I could do this over I would have went left - and walked up the exit.

At one point was 620 feet from gz. Considered bushwhacking but since I was in shorts I stayed on the trail. Eventually was .24 from gz. Kept going. Used the rope to climb up. Met a few walkers who said when I exited the rope climb not to follow the arrow but to go left. I did. Soon found myself 105 feet away … then 110 … 130… went back to 100 and bushwhacked down.   Soon had the prize. Took picks and returned it to its hiding place. 

Time up - 21 mins

Decided to take the arrow touts down. Used one of the mysteries as a waypoint and went down the slope. Made it to a dry creek bed and followed it to the water. Eventually hit the exit trail and took it around. 

Time down- 9mins

Quite an adventure. A fav. 

Thanks for the smiley. 

There’s a new cool caching group in town… check us out on Facebook: https://m.facebook.com/groups/1559902014755099/?ref=share</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.452467" lon="-71.355367"><time>2000-12-16T00:00:00</time><name>GCEC</name><desc>Brenton Point  DO NOT ATTEMPT AT NIGHT! by Adopted by RIclimber (Hidden by Bob &amp; Adena)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCEC</url><urlname>Brenton Point  DO NOT ATTEMPT AT NIGHT!</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="236" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Brenton Point  DO NOT ATTEMPT AT NIGHT!</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Adopted by RIclimber (Hidden by Bob &amp; Adena)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="73561">RIclimber</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="17" inc="1">Poisonous plants</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Rhode Island</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>***NOTE***09-03-15***&lt;br /&gt;
After another 7 years, this cache was passed to me.
&lt;p&gt;*** NOTE***08-29-08 ***&lt;br /&gt;
Since CL has moved out of the area, she has asked me to adopt this cache. Active for almost 8 years, with over 500 finds, I am thrilled to take this one over. -BBWolf&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;***NOTE***10-16-03***&lt;br /&gt;
I am very honored and happy to be taking over the maintenance of this cache. Other than this notation, the cache will remain as Bob wrote it. Jessica&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;b&gt;THIS PARK IS CLOSED DUSK TO DAWN. THAT MEANS IT IS CLOSED WHEN IT IS DARK OUT. IF I RECEIVE A SINGLE ADDITIONAL LOG THAT STATES THEY FOUND THIS GEOCACHE AFTER DARK, I WILL PERMANENTLY ARCHIVE AND REMOVE THIS CACHE!!! Don't be that person who gets the oldest cache in the state archived!&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Brenton Point is our second geocache and the first in Rhode Island. It’s located at Brenton Point State Park on the southernmost tip of Newport, Rhode Island. Find your way to downtown Newport and follow Thames Street (the main drag) until you see the signs for Ocean Drive. Follow Ocean Drive as it winds its way past the upscale homes that define Newport. After about two miles or so, you’ll pass Fort Adams State Park on your right. Soon you'll see Hammersmith Farm, the former home to the Kennedy's, also on your right. Continue and within a mile or so the rocky coast will appear on your right. Another mile or so and you will see signs for Brenton Point State Park on your left. Turn left into the state park and follow the signs for parking.
&lt;p&gt;Brenton Point is home to a wide range of outdoor activities. Many folks come here to look at the ocean, picnic, wander the trails, climb on the rocks and our favorite, fly kites. You might want to find the stone tower (N 41 deg 27.216 min W 071 deg 21.216 min (WGS-84)) located about 1/4 mile north of the parking area in the woods for a bit of a view.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is a medium-sized Lock &amp;amp; Lock.&lt;br /&gt;
- Bob &amp;amp; Adena&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="red"&gt;Winter note: Cache will be hard to locate in substantial snow.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Behind smaller rock.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364917642"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T23:03:07</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="33595760">ZombieMeow200</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Happened to be out here visiting a friend and stopped by to grab this cache with her pup </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363339519"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="49356607">CheddarBiscuit22</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Made the trip out here specifically for this cache. So wet. Much rain. Drowned rat.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363173092"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="49354510">AngusMcGrundle</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The rain won't stop us from logging this one. CheddarBiscuit and I proudly made this find, and soaked ourselves to the bone. Signed and returned to the longtime home. Nearly 26 years and counting.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362982647"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T16:37:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8724011">Candy Apple 68</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from Letchworth State Park in Mount Morris, NY!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363323204"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5445477">Albus_Birch</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found this oldie while visiting the Brenton Point area!  Thanks for keeping it going!

8038</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="33.733683" lon="-82.178533"><time>2000-12-24T00:00:00</time><name>GCF4</name><desc>Modoc Stash by Eric Stapleton</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCF4</url><urlname>Modoc Stash</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="244" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Modoc Stash</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Eric Stapleton</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1221">estapleton</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>4</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>South Carolina</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Easy follow the trail, Hard go straight.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>UPDATE 01/31/2024:
The cache is still there but it does not look like the original trail head is going to be cleaned up for a while. There are several logs that show how dedicated geocachers are! Thanks to Three Stars for showing and marking an alternative route check out their log entry.

UPDATE 05/10/2014: Thanks to IrishCubsFan for replacing the cache after the burn. It should be about 15ft west of the rock. 

ORIGINAL DESCRIPTION: It is not difficult to get to but it is about 1.2 miles down a hiking/biking trail. I called it the Modoc Stash because the trail is known as the Modoc Trail in the Sumter National Forest. I left a Geocache letter, a log book and a Beck Midnite Vultures CD. This cache has been replaced multiple times and actually moved to try to keep it from being muggled. They moved the new cache up to the top of the hill, that it was originally located on the side of, and it is now behind a large boulder (the only one up there) under a log.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364222178"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T14:25:31</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51027487">mikchicken16</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">the first word in the description is “easy” but this is not easy peasy lemon squeezy this is pifficult difficult lemon death!!! this hike is not for the faint of heart. sitting at gz now catching my breath. also going to have to go to a store and find a pair of clothes because i fell twice, twisted my knee, and scraped my arm. all that being said, i love that geocachers have made a foot trail despite the area being closed. the reward is worth the struggle for sure!! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363357375"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T22:59:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="30920028">mathmanbill</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 2 of an oldie trip with JoeBum. Today’s goals included Stone Mountain and MoDoc Stash. We had surprisingly great weather for our hike to the top. 

We couldn’t decide how serious previous logs were about the downed tree mess on the trail, so we opted to follow the nearby power line trail until it reached a perpendicular pathway. We took that for a bit, made our way down some sticky paths, and found the main trail. It took us just over an hour for the power walk/hiking experience from the trailhead parking lot. The terrain will definitely be intense for older/less fit cachers, so just beware. It’s unfortunate that the trail hasn’t been cleared off in the past two years now. TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363357078"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T22:54:09</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3588517">JoeBum</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 2 of an oldie trip with mathmanbill. Today’s goals included Stone Mountain and MoDoc Stash. We had surprisingly great weather for our hike to the top.

As we drove towards this area, we started reading all of the previous logs. It sounded tough. We had about an hour and half until sunset and the potential for rain. After looking at various options and previous logs, we opted to approach using the powerline clearing. It worked well enough. With recent rain, we were getting wet with any route. We had a total of 3 small water crossings. Our approach consisted of 1) a short run down the road after parking 2) a hike along the clearing until we found 3) a logging road 4) navigating around hurricane debris on the actual trail.

It was an adventure. No rain, but soaked clothes.

Thanks for the hide and maintaining this oldest!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362481409"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T12:26:02</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3100031">Team Michtana</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is by far the biggest geocache adventure I think I’ve ever had I have been caching before smart phones. We came here last winter was unsuccessful got deterred by all the dead fall. On my way out using the power lines as some people mentioned. I found there is a Forest Service road 632A.  This section of road is closed to motorized use. So I decided to bring back my bike this year 1 mile in and out on the bike. Then a .3 mile hike each way. Some might say it’s cheating when I say it’s being smart.  Besides, don’t knock it until you try there’s still a ton of dead fall you gotta climb over and this time of year there is plenty of poison everything.   </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361466697"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-16T11:54:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1547165">tbly</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#30 oldest US state cache found
Goal cache for this trip and a slight detour from my route south. Parked at the trailhead and bushwacked about .25mi before finding the trail among all of the downed trees. About 2 hours round trip. Thanks for keeping this one active and for a good workout.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.96495" lon="-103.83748333333334"><time>2001-05-01T00:00:00</time><name>GC87F</name><desc>Campcache by ERH-IN-WI</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC87F</url><urlname>Campcache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="2175" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Campcache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>ERH-IN-WI</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="2501">ERH-IN-WI</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Not chosen</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>4</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>South Dakota</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>On top of a cliff overlooking the Ditch Creek Campground(good fishin) in the Black Hills NF.  Good veiw. </groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Cache is an ammo can with www.geocaching.com written all over it.  Inside you will find misc. stuff including CD's for Garmin(r&amp;r, metro).&lt;p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.wi-geocaching.com" target="wga"&gt;
&lt;img src="http://www.wi-geocaching.com/banners/banner-small.gif"&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/center&gt; 



</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Take the atv trail switchbacks up to the level of the cliff and then walk back along the cliff.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364732231"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T15:06:37</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5221874">iceberrrrg</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with MuggleMomma on a trip to Kansas and Colorado. This was an adventure.  After pouring rain the night before, it made the hike pretty muddy on the way up.  Lots of trees down on top of the cliff which made the bushwhack even more challenging.  Made it to the cache and after a few picks, headed down. Just made it to the car and then the rains came.  Epic oldie Thanks for placing this Cache!! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364732703"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T15:03:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="33528440">MuggleMomma</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a road trip with iceberrrrg from northern Minnesota to Geowoodstock XXll then off to CO, NM and back to MN. 
Day 12. This one was the goal for today.  We had a short window due to the approaching storms.  So we had breakfast and headed out.  Got to the parking at about 10am. It was supposed to rain around noon so we had to make it quick.  There were heavy rain storms all night before so the trail had many big puddles to go around and the trail was super greasy.  As we approached GZ we could hear the storms rumbling.  We made the find quickly, posed for a photo, slammed down some water and headed back.  Got to the car, changed out of our muddy boots and headed out at 12:30.  About a mile down the road the rain started. So happy we made it before or we would have slid down that muddy path!   This was quite the adventure!  I am sure I will feel it for a couple days.  Lol. Favorite for sure.  
Thanks for placing this cache and for adding to the fun!  </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364265565"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5135545">smitranm</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">[:)] Day fifteen of two week road trip GeoWoodstock XXII in Kansas as the main goal. Rapid City, SD to Miles City, MT. Mostly cloudy with cooler weather in mountains. Later hot. Ten finds and a DNF. Thank you for the cache. A favorite.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364264288"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5135553">smitranp</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Followed instructions from previous logs and had no problem.
[:)] Two oldest in South Dakota took half a day. After that it was mostly driving with a couple of stops. Most of the finds were made in Miles City. Thank you for the cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363252811"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T11:32:31</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47911">medicineman</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Took our time on the rocky switchback. Had a false start towards the final and redirected. No matter what, last 750 feet were a chore coming and going. The view at the end was spectacular. Perfect weather today too. Signed the lig and left a path tag and a TB </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="35.08615" lon="-89.6706"><time>2001-01-06T00:00:00</time><name>GC132</name><desc>LPS001 by LPS</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC132</url><urlname>LPS001</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="306" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>LPS001</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>LPS</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="56853">bitbrain</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="38" inc="0">Campfires</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="11" inc="1">May require wading</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Tennessee</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;b&gt;First Geocache in Tennessee&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
Located within a park near a man made trail. LPS has moved away from the area, bitbrain has adopted and is maintaining this cache. This is Tennessee's first cache, let's help preserve it. Photos of the cache are welcome. LPS no longer lives in TN but would enjoy a photo from time to time.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;center&gt;Park is open until 11pm every day.&lt;/center&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You will need to leave the boardwalk to find this cache, but please follow the boardwalk to the Deer Crossing before heading off into the woods.&lt;/strong&gt; .&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Please take care when hunting, retrieving and replacing this cache. You are in the fetid swamps of Elvisland and the natural inhabitants may be near the cache. Snakes, spiders, rabbits, deer, etc...&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
When you reseal the container, please make sure there's nothing in the seal to allow water to seep in. When you rehide the container, please verify that it is secure.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size:9px;"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Original text of cache description:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
This is my first Geocache. I used a large baby formula can to place my items in it. It is easy to locate and only 25 meters from a boardwalk. The altitude of the geocache is 111 meters. Enjoy the park and the scenic views. The logbook contains notes about the Geocache as well as a location of a great hiking area.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:9px;"&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Geocache originally contained:&lt;br /&gt;
1. Logbook&lt;br /&gt;
2. Pencil&lt;br /&gt;
3. Pen from a previous employer&lt;br /&gt;
4. Two lightbulbs from a $100,000 Eskofot Copydot Film Scanner&lt;br /&gt;
5. 4mm DAT tape containing Scitex data&lt;br /&gt;
6. Three dessicant packs&lt;br /&gt;
7. Calculator&lt;br /&gt;
8. Maglite&lt;br /&gt;
9. Calendar Page&lt;br /&gt;
10. Stashnote.doc&lt;br /&gt;
11. Screwdriver&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>crotch of triple tree</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364912912"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T19:49:43</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="56853">bitbrain</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">From the Town of Collierville:

Beginning June 15, 2026, the entire Johnson Park boardwalk will close to the public for the summer season to undergo structural repairs and renovations. 

The project contract specifies a 110-day timeline, making the anticipated completion date October 3, 2026. Crews will replace the original 1,000-foot section of the boardwalk, built back in 2000, stretching from the Nature Center to the gazebo. While the newer section is still in good shape, we have to close the entire boardwalk to keep everyone safe while heavy equipment is moving. 

Why are doing this during a busy, boardwalk season? This trail sits in a wetland, and we have to do the work during the drier summer months when the ground is solid enough for construction crews.

Our Public Works Director, Josh Russell, wants trail users to know we are doing everything we can to speed up the process: "We are hopeful that it won't take that long. We're working to get the message out now so everyone who enjoys this trail will have plenty of notice."

Thank you for your patience while we give this well-loved trail a much-needed upgrade! We will provide project updates as needed.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363938003"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T15:15:45</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1906272">mdsearcher</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice muggy hike to the cache today.  Left the boardwalk to hike through mosquito heaven to reach the prize. TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363768572"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T14:05:44</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42809914">tela42499</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It's a muggy one out here today. The boardwalk can be slippery. Be careful. This is my last oldie on my way home from geowoodstock. Wear bug spray or regret it like I did. Thank you from Asheville for keeping this one alive</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363810065"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4941578">2KatzHunt</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">OMG!! Holy Mosquitos!! We are on our way home from Geo-Woodstock finding Oldies, Cache Odysseys, counties and anything that strikes our fancy.  This was on our Must Do list. I arrived and didn't realize there was a boardwalk most of the way to the cache.  One would think that a boardwalk would be an advantage, but it definately was NOT. It had rained this morning and the boardwalk is so slimy from moss and algea that walking was a real chore.  I walked on the boardwalk to where the trail marker was on the map. The trail marker was a place that they had fashioned a 'deer crossing', sign and all. All they did was cut the railing for about 8' so the deer can more easily cross over the boardwalk.  I bushwacked from there because I saw no trail to follow.  

I found the cache, but it was a real chore. I had to keep backtracking to avoid multiple water hazards. I came back making a straight line from the cache back to the boardwalk and did not encounter any water or even any soggy places, 388'.  I had to climb over the railing, but that was much easier than avoiding all the water I found on the way to the cache. Oh, and the mosquitos were soooo bad, I have no idea what I will look like tomorrow. 

It gets a favorite point for being our 38th oldest in state.....TFTC

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364079976"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="216131">bbatch6</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The GA HICS (consisting of bbatch6, Maddog1973, Team Sheppard, Harbor Spy, Lazer, Insanesimmer, Fernweh3, joebids, and Greydirk) went to Geowoodstock XXII! And, of course, we cached along the way! We targeted counties, oldest caches and other special or high favorite caches. This means we are did a lot of meandering around and lots of detours were involved. Some detours were planned and others just happened.
Once we arrived even more caching went on. We did the Adventure Labs. We completed the Rocket Geoart where we were joined by the CHAT group. While touring the salt mine, the zoo and the space museum we did virtual caches, earthcaches and anything else in the area. We had a wonderful time!
On the return trip we got more counties as we traveled home. There was less detouring but there was still some. All in all it was an exhausting but wonderful trip! We're all looking forward to next year! Caches are signed GA HICS or HICS/CHAT.
We are so glad to finally have this oldest cache!  We actually got a cache not far from here back in 2006 but at that time we knew nothing about county caching or getting oldest caches.  Too bad, we could have had it 20 years ago.  But better late than never!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="32.727033" lon="-97.116017"><time>2000-09-26T00:00:00</time><name>GC62</name><desc>Tombstone by HackAttack and Ma Bell</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC62</url><urlname>Tombstone</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Multi-cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="98" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Tombstone</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>HackAttack and Ma Bell</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="43361">HackAttack</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Multi-cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="0">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="0">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="59" inc="1">Food nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="58" inc="1">Fuel nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Texas</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Multi-Cache located in a park in Arlington. First two stages are very geoferret friendly. Last stage is questionable.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font face="OldCentury" size="5"&gt;" Tombstone "&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font color="red"&gt;&lt;font size="+2"&gt;DO NOT ENTER GRAVEYARD TO GET THE CACHE! There is no need to enter the graveyard to get to the cache.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;This is a multi-cache all within one park, with very minimal walking. You must use the coordinates for this cache page to lead you to the 1st Stage. You will need to decrypt this stage to complete your Latitude coordinates. After finishing the 1st Stage, precede to the 2nd Stage coordinates written below. You will need to decrypt this clue to get your Longitude coordinates.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font size="4" color="#FF0000"&gt;1st Stage&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font size="4" color="#000000"&gt;:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; The cache page coordinates will take you to a Historical Marker along the sidewalk. You're looking for the coaches name:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;The coach's name was: Easterling&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;The Latitude coordinates are: N32 43.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="#FF0000" size="4"&gt;2nd Stage&lt;/font&gt;:&lt;/b&gt; The coodinates for the second stage are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;N32 43.716&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;W097 07.018&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;The coordinates for the second stage will take you to a spot along the fence line outside a graveyard, inside the park. Please do not enter the graveyard. From outside the fence look for a tombstone with McBride on it. Look for the child's name that lived from 1902-1904. Take the FIRST name of this individual and decrypt it to find the coodinates to the final cache:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;The child's name was &lt;b&gt;Dewey&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;The Longitude coordinates are: W097 07.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="4" color="#184A74"&gt;Use the following to decrypt the names:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="4" color="#FB7D00"&gt;A=5 B=2 C=0 D=7 E=9 F=3 G=6 I=2 J=7 K=6 L=2 M=7 N=3 O=4 P=5 Q=4 R=1 S=2 T=9 U=0 V=4 W=8 Y=3 Z=2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font size="4" color="#FF0000"&gt;Find the Cache&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;font color="#000000" size="3"&gt;&lt;b&gt;:&lt;/b&gt; To find the cache simply finish the Longitude and Latitude coordinates:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;&lt;b&gt;N32 43.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font size="4"&gt;(&lt;b&gt;First Name&lt;/b&gt; of the Coach)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="5"&gt;&lt;b&gt;W097 07.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font size="4"&gt;(&lt;b&gt;First Name&lt;/b&gt; of the Child)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;Please note the final cache is located in the same park. If final coordinates take you more than 1/10th of a mile away - you did something wrong.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;Parking may be a little more difficult during the week unless you want to pay meter parking. There are still places to park but you may have to walk a little. On the weekend there is parking right next to the cache and it is free on weekends according to the site page below. https://www.uta.edu/pats/parking/visitor-parking.php&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="4"&gt;Cache is Decon container size.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table align="center"&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;a href="http://info.flagcounter.com/mu3t"&gt;&lt;img src="http://s06.flagcounter.com/count/mu3t/bg_FFFFFF/txt_000000/border_CCCCCC/columns_4/maxflags_12/viewers_0/labels_0/pageviews_0/flags_0/" alt="Flag Counter" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>No bushwacking required at all now</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364386730"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13654265">*Mana*</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache is older than the finder!

GC62 was placed in September 2000. Paul, who found it today, was not born yet. A quarter of a century later, a young geocacher from North Carolina finally came to pay his respects to one of Texas' geocaching pioneers.

We loved the classic multi-cache format and the feeling of travelling back to the early days of the hobby. No smartphones back then, no fancy apps, just coordinates, clues and adventure.

The incredible history behind this cache definitely earned it a Favorite Point from us.

Thank you ***HackAttack*** for keeping this geocaching veteran alive and well.

Greetings from a French family enjoying an unforgettable Texas road trip!
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364375914"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="14481342">PSCM</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">OCW *Mana * 
Temp log
Fav!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364434556"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T10:46:38</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5970043">schoenecker</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I had this Multi for a long time on my bucket list.
Answers had been solved via online research, but then I paused Geocaching for a bit. As I am now back in action, I remembered this one and definitely wanted to go here while being in Dallas.
I parked my car in the shadows of the trees close by the bridge (weekends free of charge), and from there it was an easy walk to the Final.
Great to find one of the oldest geocaches!

Thanks a lot for the many years of maintenance!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364255066"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T17:43:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5988973">Sypes</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for the hide! I was able to track down Tombstone. The streak lives on another day. Thank you to HackAttack for your contributions to this wonderful hobby that we share!

Sypes #2520
May 29, 2026

“To see the world, things dangerous to come to, to see behind walls, to draw closer, to find each other and to feel. That is the purpose of life.”</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364512270"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T11:11:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1328776">Sol de lune</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**THIS CACHE - DAY 13**

After the fun of Geowoodstock at Hutchinson KS, we headed out for Colby to Colorado Springs, Truth or Consequences, Pecos and now Fort Worth.   Today is out day in the US and we fly out tonight at 11.00pm.   Lots of caches found Dallas/Fort Worth and all were found without issue.    

This was a special cache to find being the oldest in Texas...and a multi to boot.   Fav point added

Thanks for the fun and the caches HackAttack   Logs stamped as Aussies on Walkabout if required.

**THE TRIP**

Geowoodstock XXII - Hutchinson Kansas 2026.

Headed over from Australia to attend the next installment of Geowoodstock with LuckyL10n and McLookers. Arrived into Dallas to start our road on Saturday 16th May, driving through Texas, Louisiana, Arkansas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Colorado, New Mexico, Texas again, Mexico, Texas again and then up to Dallas on the 30 May to fly home. The plan is to grab at least one cache in as many counties as possible. Another neat little road trip around a few US states.


</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="546655413"><groundspeak:date>2015-10-04T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Stopped by here on the way home from Family Day at UT Dallas.  I had already solved for the final coordinates before and was unsuccessful in finding a way to GZ from outside the fence.

In any case, i'm really stoked that today we were able to add Texas to our list of states we've found the oldest active cache in.  I'm really glad this one is still here and active after all these years.

Cache On!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="39.44905" lon="-111.276833"><time>2000-08-27T00:00:00</time><name>GC3B</name><desc>Potters Pond by leaper64 &amp; dirk88</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC3B</url><urlname>Potters Pond</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="59" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Potters Pond</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>leaper64 &amp; dirk88</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="42">leaper64</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="0">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="0">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="37" inc="1">Horses</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="1">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="0">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Utah</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>This is one of my favorite places and I think you'll agree that
it's a fitting place for the first cache placed in the state of
Utah. After you find the stash, relax a little and wet a hook in
Potters Pond. You'll catch your fill of pan-sized trout using
Rainbow, Lemon Twist or Green power-bait.
&lt;p&gt;If you are planning on staying in the Potter's Pond campground,
its a good idea to get a reservation. The reservation number is
1-877-444-6777.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note: there is heavy winter snow cover in this area during
winter months.&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>under one of those trees.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364921647"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1271259">NitiFlex</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Ritorno a questa bellissima cache con i logbook originali dell'agosto 2000. 
Stavolta sono con Laura. In questo anno  sono successe tantissimi cose tristi. 
Il pensiero di chi ci ha spero rimanga in eterno con questa scatola del tempo in questo posto in pace.
Non posso dare un'altro punto favorito ma lascio 3 TB e prelevo tutti i presenti.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364846521"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8847997">after8</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I must thank my geobuddy NitiFlex who is coming back after one year for me to sign my 3rd Jasmer. 
Many fallen tree. One is useful to cross the creek. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364759682"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4350112">jasperdakota</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with geodog Riley. Nice to finally grab this oldie. Left 17 TBs and a couple of pathtags. Picked up the only one TB in the cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364120187"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4281915">Go-pher-It</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Pammy24VT,  fragavWA and Go-pher-It came to Potters Pond today. We encountered small patches of snow on the drive up, saw several deer 🦌 and briefly spoke to a park ranger.  We enjoyed the views and fragavWA found the cache. This is the fourth time that I have come up here and the third time that I walked up to the cache hide. Thank you leaper64 for placing and maintaining this oldie but goodie.  Today we signed the logbook at 1025 hours. Cache is on great condition 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364102260"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T10:36:43</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="36292886">pammy24VT</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We made it what an adventure to reach our destination. Over water over trees up we go. We saw a few mule deer not sure who startled who. We saw evidence of elk in the area with several piles of elk scat on our path or is it their path. I took my shoes and socks off and waded through the stream. A little chilly but felt good on my achy toes. The cache was located in great condition. Looked through the logs a left or marks. Over all a great day. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.16" lon="-73.013517"><time>2000-10-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC86</name><desc>Vermont 1 by GPS Guy and Michael McNeany</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC86</url><urlname>Vermont 1</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Multi-cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="134" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Vermont 1</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>GPS Guy and Michael McNeany</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="340">GPS Guy</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Multi-cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Vermont</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>DO NOT DRIVE UP THE TRAIL!!! Updated 8/22/25. Print these directions and bring them and a compass with you. Trade only hiking or survival items, please! Learn to project waypoints! Logs with spoiler photos or step sizes will be deleted. Sorry.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Clue: Go To the coordinates ( also in UTM 18T 0661496 4780498) to find "Observation Rock." From there take a bearing of 318 degrees and walk 140 steps. Take a new bearing of 090 degrees and go 100 steps to a boulder. Turn to 332 degrees and walk 120 steps. Start looking. The cache is hidden by a layer of branches and leaves.
&lt;p&gt;Comments: The first cache in Vermont, (Hence the name) and for many miles beyond when we placed it.(See waypoint number above.) We hope that you will enjoy finding it. There is parking and a trail head about a mile North of the cache near a water tank. Park along the road (obey no parking signs) or use high ground clearance vehicle to reach the 2 parking spots just up the trail at the trailhead sign.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When you have finished your hunt, you may hike further up the main trail to Prospect Rock, which has a USGS Benchmark and a view of Manchester. If you find the cache, please be sure to leave something related to hiking/survival if you take something, make a log entry, and when you get home, let us know of your success and how difficult you felt it was to find the cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Addendum- 8/17/02- The bucket,log book, and contents have been replaced due to water damage. A third leg has been added to the cache hunt directions. Contents all have a hiking/survival theme. Please only trade items of this type. Thanks! 5/8/06 Bucket changed to another container.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>True Bearings. Don't go over the edge!</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364421151"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T14:00:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3218412">twistedchickie</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Live close by and finally made the trex here on this brisk day .. nice hike up took about 40 mins or so .. and nice view .. thanks for this oldie!! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363895907"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:28:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8724011">Candy Apple 68</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from Letchworth State Park in Mount Morris, NY!!  Beautiful; Beautiful!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363961881"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5445477">Albus_Birch</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">After a night spent in Burlington, we headed down this morning for this one.  

Parking - we parked at N 43 10.326, W 073 00.731 by the water tower.  We did drive past to look at the road, but we were skeptical about the Forester's ground clearance.  

A nice hike up with us taking a few photos.  We took the correct trail over to the start.  First projection took us to a trail, which seemed reasonable.  Second projection took us past a few boulders.  Hmm.  Third projection took us near the final area, which together with the hint, we found about 70 feet away.  

YAY!  Another oldie in the books in a beautiful location!  Favorite point!

8064</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363783853"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T16:20:05</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1810758">ReidRick</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Needed a little help since my projection came up a little short but soon found the cache </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360935692"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-13T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="14566146">CheekyBrit</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Did anyone else park at N 43° 10.327' W 073°  00.930' or am i missing a trick? I get the impression that there is much better parking available.I just don't know it. View from observation rock is absolutely staggering , and that alone earns a favorite point. The bearing and distance portion was a bit difficult since my steps were thirty to forty percent bigger than the puzzle is designed for. I ended up about some 60 feet away from where the final ended up being.But as I expanded my search radius without going off the edge , I was able to come up with the goods. Yellow dogs beat me b to it today.And they have been ahead of me on many , many new england geocaches. I'm not following you guys, honest. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="703502208"><groundspeak:date>2017-07-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I'd love to get my scout troop up here for orienteering practice.  What a great exercise.

I'm very glad I rented the 4x4 to make this trip. Well worth it!

Pictures will come later.
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="37.000117" lon="-81.000033"><time>2001-01-06T00:00:00</time><name>GC135</name><desc>Elvis Confluence by Craig Ferguson  (adopted by DMFlyer) </desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC135</url><urlname>Elvis Confluence</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="309" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Elvis Confluence</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Craig Ferguson  (adopted by DMFlyer) </groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="159269">DMflyer</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Not chosen</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="0">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="1">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="22" inc="1">Hunting area</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>4</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Virginia</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This geocache is located at a confluence point of N37 00.000 and W81 00.000 degrees, in the Jefferson National Forest. 2.3 miles (3.7 km) NE of Stringtown, VA, USA.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Terrain is rugged and access is limited by private landholdings surrounding the forest. There are many routes, get a landowner's permission before crossing their land, and leave gates as you find them. This cache was inspired by the confluence game at &lt;a href="http://www.confluence.org"&gt;Confluence.org&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Original container was a plastic, 5-gallon, white paint bucket wrapped in a garbage bag. Stickers denoting the Geocache and the confluence coordinates were on the outside. Many cool prizes awaited this somewhat difficult cache. The landowners we found were very nice. It was a fun afternoon. Schedule a day.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font color="teal"&gt;NOTE: Cache has been replaced and moved to a nearby spot!&lt;br /&gt;
Cache is now a .50 cal Ammo box painted primer brown. Side has GEOCACHE painted on it&lt;br /&gt;
New co-ordinates posted on 26 Mar 2005!&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.groundspeak.com/cache/faa6f885-317c-40e2-9ef4-66a591c54d91.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
Helpful hints:&lt;br /&gt;
Schedule a day, leave the bubbateeth at home, and don't forget to turn on the GPS (duh)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Note: Access to Jefferson National Forest land can be reached without crossing private property !&lt;br /&gt;
Most other routes require landowner permisson.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
From VA 712 find rock painted red at: N37 00.784 W080 57.391&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Along VA712, there is about 400ft of frontage along the road that is Jefferson National Forest land.&lt;br /&gt;
Waypoints:&lt;br /&gt;
Park near disk marked WC 18.48 National Forest Service&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
If you stay between the 'Do Not Trespass' signs and the red blazed trees at the top of the ridge, its farily easy. There is an old ATV trail you will be following once you reach FS1 waypoint.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Some waypoints of Forest Service Benchmarks:&lt;br /&gt;
Other markers with red painted bands around trees nearby:&lt;br /&gt;
FS1 N37 00.675 W080 57.662&lt;br /&gt;
FS2 N37 00.643 W080 58.270&lt;br /&gt;
FS3 N37 00.487 W080 58.981&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Steep elevation change from parking to top of ridge. Unless your a camel and can go all day without water, come prepared. Bring water, food and a camera! The views from on top are phenomenal.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Please respect private property, do not trespass without landowner permission. The locals are friendly but most are not likely to allow access across their property due to hunters with ATV's trespassing in the past. The Sherrif Department is aware of the problem with ATV's&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;b&gt;Please do not leave any food products or anything that smells like food (i.e. fruit scented items). Animals will find and destroy the cache if you do. Thanks.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.gsmgc.net" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="http://img.groundspeak.com/cache/62a396ba-0e1d-4e06-b705-e2e43a59f569.jpg" width="414" alt="Great Smokey Mountain Geocaching Club" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/email/?guid=0217c6a3-d3f9-4c71-a967-69923d6f5185" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="http://img.groundspeak.com/cache/3bf9f8b5-34b7-4163-aea9-c36803ed52ca.jpg" alt="____" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;table border="0"&gt;&lt;/table&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>in end of a hollow log</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1360634534"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-12T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="34751">bigcall</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I saw that reedkickball!!!

I'll admit this one was a lot more fun though too</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359814250"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T12:26:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="19483995">Aegir101</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Today I teamed up with MJBinski and reedkickball to tackle Elvis Confluence an impressive 25 year-old cache on a ridge in SW VA. We got up at 0330 and were on the road at 0415 for the 4+ hr drive south. We have been trying to do this one for a while and got cancelled by a snowstorm back in Feb which was a bummer. Today it was in the 60s sunny and no humidity. The rhododendrons and some mountain laurels and azaleas were in bloom, the birds were singing and it was beautiful. We parked at red rock and hiked 9.24 mi with 1792’ in elevation gain in 4 hours and found all the caches on the ridge. Thanks to all these COs for placing and maintaining these caches. 
     This was an amazing cache. This was one of the toughest but one of my most favorite hikes in VA up there with Moonshine Mountain Devils Backbone, Buzzard Ridge and The Tombs. I like these challenging climbs and this had a fair bit of bushwhacking too. We struggled up the ridge to start. At the top there was a deer trail that opened up to an okd toad we followed this for a while and saw the FS waypoints. The road divided and we wisely took the upper branch. This finally died out about 0.7 mi from cache and there was a lot of small pine trees that made slow going but we went right to the ridge and found a deer trail that opened up more as we got closer to GZ. We foubd the elbow tree and made a waypoint near the cache. After detouring to the puzzle we hiked back 30 min and descended to GZ. We did not drop into the ravine since we had read previous logs and after a brief search I spotted it the coords were very tight. Awesome find, so happy to find VA’s (real) oldest. This was much more satisfying than Burke lake. Huge fave point! AIO, TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360624201"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="764956">reedkickball</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">So is this the oldest geocache in Virginia or not? Honestly, I don’t know… and I don’t particularly care, because whichever one holds the title, I’ve found both. 😄

That being said, this one is clearly the better cache. Just don’t tell the CO of the other “oldest cache” I said that.

A little advice for future finders: don’t do what I did and charge up the mountain like you’re trying to set a land-speed record. Take it slow and steady. Otherwise, you too can enjoy gasping for air and developing a lovely dry cough for the rest of the day. Whoever designed gravity really overachieved on that hill.

Once we reached the first cache, the terrain for most of the hike was actually pretty reasonable… except for the delightful little descent and climb back up the slope for this cache. 

The scenery was fantastic though. The whole area was covered in pink flowers, and we kept spotting pile after pile after pile of bear scat near the berry bushes. Eventually it stopped being a question of if we’d see a bear and became when. Thankfully, we had a Viking (MJBinski) with us. History has shown that 
Bears are notoriously ineffective against Vikings.

As for the cache itself, it was an easy find once we arrived. We snapped the obligatory photos commemorating our discovery of “the oldest geocache in the state” (terms and conditions may apply), then began the trek back. And that hill somehow felt even steeper on the way down.

TNLN. Thanks for keeping this cache going for so many years!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360360455"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6605723">MJBinski</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">### **Elvis Confluence** ###

---

Found with **reedkickball** and **Aegir101.**  

Similar to the "Which came first — The Chicken or the Egg" debate, it's hard to really know if _THIS_ is Virginia's oldest cache or if _"Burke Lake Park" (GC175)_ is Virginia's oldest cache. There are a bunch of different opinions and ways to look at it, but in the end, does it really matter? _"Elvis Confluence" (GC135)_ will always register in my mind as Virginia's second oldest cache, but _THIS_ is clearly the better of the two caches. After finding this cache, I'm still left with a couple of questions, though.

Why is it called ELVIS Confluence?

&amp;

Why isn't it located at the actual confluence?

Not really important, but these were two questions I kept fixating on during the many hours of hiking we did today.

Today's adventure was EPIC! It was so much fun to do this as a group with two of my caching comrades. As I mentioned in a log from a previous cache find today, this adventure really made me realize how out of shape I've become. I've been retired from the Army for almost 10 years now, and the only exercise I really get these days is while I'm geocaching. Of course, that involves a lot of hiking, biking, kayaking, etc., but still. 

I'm not where I used to be or where I want to be physically. I think this adventure will set me on a path to improve my physical fitness. I mean, there are a lot of people in worse shape than I am, but we are our own worst critics.

I digress... 

I had planned to come here back in February for my 20,000th find, but a snow/ice storm prevented that from happening. I REALLY wanted to make this a milestone find, but it just wouldn't have been safe. Considering I live 4.5 hours away from here, just getting to the parking area would've been an adventure in itself. Even if we did make it, I think the snow and ice on the hills and the ridge would've prevented us from finding the cache (let alone even making it to the cache location). 

This is/was another _'bucket list'_ cache for me, and I'm so glad we got it done today! Almost 5 hours of hiking and over 9 hours of driving, but it was totally worth it! We also took advantage of the opportunity and made two stops at Buc-ee's in Rockingham.

Thanks for the amazing adventure! The memory of today will remain for years and years to come! Adding a ♥ FAVORITE POINT ♥ and a handful of photos.
    
---

Thanks to **DMflyer** for placing and maintaining this cache!

**Found at 12:26 PM on Friday, 08 May 2026** 

**MJB...** 🤡</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1356587407"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1890693">Mitovirginia</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it..   WOW.!!! It’s amazing.  It’s Tiring.  Now.!!  I'm able to say that -  I DID IT.!!!  
I tried to get others to come but ended up going by Myself ... I still had a great time.!!  
I got to the RED ROCK late. And Headed up the Mountain at 11AM instead of 10.30 AM 
I made sure I had enough Water. Gatorade and snacks with me.  
And anything else that I needed for the day with me in my backpack... 
 Grabbed my walking stick.   
This body is Not in Shape but  I Managed..  And took me an Extra Few Hours to Complete...  
It took 4 hours to get to the End.  or to Challenge Cache and Another 2 and half hours back.  
Down the hill OR should I say DOWN the "MOUNTAIN"...  6 and half  Total...!! 
I followed a lot of what  ~ Honu58  ~  Did to stay on the trail Stay on TOP.!! 
There was a lot of brush that once on top I went from side to side trying to go Forward…
I wish they allowed the 4-wheeler back up the Mountain..  They would help keep the trail 
cleaned up better… 
There's trees down.  Where you have to climb over or go around which means you have to
dip down and around the trees. Then back up a small incline of the Mountain. To Stay Up On Top.  
Then to get through the Brush… The 4-wheelers would probably Help to get a Better Trail,. 
For people that want to walk/ hike/ climb the hill.  Opp's MOUNTAIN.!!... 
Favorite added and TFTC… 😊  I DID IT.!!! GOOD LUCK TO THE NEXT CACHER.!!  
Had to Come back and Say I got  3900 YAAA... Didn't Realize that I got it there...
 I knew I was getting Close to 3900.  BUT,  That's Great.!!  Fabulous. Fantastic.
 That just Topped the Frosting on the CAKE...!!  

 A friend Asked,   How my trip went, because they couldn’t make it.??  
I thought about it and responded back with the following.: 

I had a Great Time… It was Looong… It was tiring. … I was by myself… Elvis is No Joke.!! 
Once at the Three Tree.. YOU Head DOWN 500 FT to Elvis…. Straight Down.!! 
Then Back up the MOUNTAIN to continue your trip. On up to the Challenge Cache…

It was Well Earned. Well Deserved… Very Valuable Day…Well Worth the TRIP…
 GC135.!! Glad, That I was able to do it… You may read my above log…
Took me … 6 ½ Hrs. To complete from Start to Finish… The sun was going down at the top 
of the Mountain When I was coming down. Also… 
If you look at my Pictures in my log and you can see the Sun and the Shadows. 
It was very Rewarding Day… … Thank you for asking…. 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="37.684776666666664" lon="-81.93386166666667"><time>2001-02-25T00:00:00</time><name>GC3F0</name><desc>Rich Creek Riches by redseal</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC3F0</url><urlname>Rich Creek Riches</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1008" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Rich Creek Riches</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>redseal</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="5114">redseal</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Not chosen</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>West Virginia</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:long_description>The stash can be reached by ATV via the Hatfield-McCoy Trail system or on foot. You do not need climbing gear but if you walk it be prepared to burn a few calories.
 &lt;p&gt;
The closest town is Gilbert, WV  25621
 &lt;p&gt;
4 or 5 prizes</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Tree</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364888173"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T15:55:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3873131">CinciChewbacca</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**This Cache**
The coveted **Rich Creek Riches.** There are a lot of unknowns with this cache no matter how many Cachers you’ve talked to that have done it. That is exactly what makes it so tricky. Based on everything I heard I just went in with plenty of time to allow for the long back road driving and hiking that would be needed for this cache.

Buckeye summarized our crazy adventure very well. We parked at N 037° 41.359' W 081° 57.025' and walked from there. We later heard that Hatfield McCoy has recently purchased the stretch of road we drove in on so it may no longer be as viable of an option but we had no troubles.

I didn’t track exactly but it was likely a little over 2 miles of trails from there before we made it to this famous cache. Contents are in great shape- thanks for keeping this legacy alive and giving us this incredible adventure with [@Buckeye](https://www.geocaching.com/p/default.aspx?u=Buckeye "@Buckeye") . Chewy FP!

**This Trip**
A weekend of adventuring through KY, TN, VA, NC, WV, and OH with goals of getting 2 tri-points, highest point in KY and VA, and the coveted oldest cache in WV! The windy roads aren’t going to stop us this weekend! 

**Thanks for placing this cache! 🇺🇸 #21865**

Cheers redseal! 💰💸💵💶💷💴🪙
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364760510"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10935665">Buckeye</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#18,000

As with any state oldest, this one has been on my radar for a while. Of the state oldests, it's probably the most challenging to reach. Even though I've lived in West Virginia for three years, I hadn't made an effort to grab it since everyone I knew had done it years ago (or used my WVU tuition money to pay for their own ATV rental). I graduated from WVU this semester, which means my days in West Virginia are now limited to caching trips. With my departure from the Mountain State, I wasn't sure if I was EVER going to get this one.

[@CinciChewbacca](https://coord.info/PR4KT3M) mentioned that he might be willing to try and off-road back to this cache, and I was for sure game! We made plans to meet up this morning in Gilbert and set off for Rich Creek Road (as I had heard you could drive to within a couple hundred feet of the cache). Chewy had identified another route that might've been the better choice, but hindsight is 20/20. Chewydad skillfully got the Subaru down Rich Creek Road to a nice wide spot and we set off on foot to the cache. It was about 1.5-2 miles to GZ, and boy was it uphill. Luckily Chewy is a good friend and was patient while I took a few breaks as we climbed the hill. After a while, we finally reached the top of the mountain and followed a decent two-track all the way back to the prize. Took some celebratory photos, signed the log, and left an unactivated trackable from the GWXXI crew before replacing everything as found and heading back to the Subaru. We only saw a few groups of ATVs out this morning and luckily we made it out unscathed.

Many thanks for a nice cache to celebrate a milestone at! I'd say after finding this one I can call myself a true Mountaineer (even if it took me until after graduation to get around to it - oops!)

I’m spending the weekend in Southeastern Kentucky and picking up a few new counties! On this trip, I’ll also be visiting Black Mountain, Cumberland Gap, and the Hatfield-McCoy trail system. Thanks for adding to my adventure!

**Rich Creek Riches**
Find #18000

Thanks for the Traditional cache, redseal!
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362066124"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T21:55:12</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="56569">xrayrepairdude</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a road trip around the SE. states to do some sightseeing, find States Oldest caches, Cache Odyssey caches, getting counties as needed as we pass through and a long list of other interesting caches all while having a grand adventure as we go!

This was an EPIC trek to the cache. We rented an ATV from BAC Country and drove ourselves to the cache. We opted to park the ATV about 500’ from the cache due to the terrain. We know the ATV was capable of going but with our minimal experience driving ATVs we figured the safest (and potentially cheapest) option was to walk the last 500’! 😜 Amber at BAC was superbly helpful and so friendly! High praise and recommendation for sure!

This is our 12th states oldest cache and certainly a memorable one! FP awarded for keeping this oldie going and for the adventure we had getting there!

Thank you redseal for the Traditional cache. This is number 9587 for us. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359648019"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-07T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="24105670">NanoBanana</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is my 26th state oldest find! What an incredible place and an incredible adventure to get here. There was much more elevation gain than I expected given the trail is marked easy on my map. I'm glad I'm doing this when I'm in good hiking shape. This is definitely one of the highlights of this entire trip. I'm also surprised that apparently none of my friends have found this one yet. The day is gorgeous and the forest looks so fresh after the recent train. I wish I had more time to explore the area. Thanks for hiding and maintaining this gem. 
All is well here. Thanks for the cache! 
@9:48 AM #14305</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357171274"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-25T17:06:02</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="50810835">Dawson_Clan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">In good shape</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1301041261"><groundspeak:date>2025-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Epic journey to WV’s oldest just a couple of days after torrential rain fall that washed out sections Rich Road.  We’d originally planned to do this on our own, but at the guidance of the proprietor of BAC ATV rentals, we joined a group they were leading up the mountain.

That turned out to be a good thing as we popped a tire and another ATV driver flagged us down to tell us.  Jessica shuttled us up the last thousand feet or so in the other ATVs we were lucky to be with. While we found and signed the cache, Jessica call in for a rescue from Amber.

On the slow way down with the flat tire, we meet up with Amber who field patched the tire and soon had us on our way.  Epic indeed!

Found with TAZ427, KodyDog00, and scottberks along side the larger group of hallycat, CP950, L8210S, alliebaba40thieves and ActionTrinity.  With the assistance of Jessica and Amber from the outfitters. 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.313067" lon="-88.310867"><time>2001-03-02T00:00:00</time><name>GC3B1</name><desc>Pike Powder Hike by kbraband</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC3B1</url><urlname>Pike Powder Hike</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="945" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Pike Powder Hike</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>kbraband</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="4841">kbraband</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="0">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="0">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="9" inc="1">Significant hike</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="0">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="36" inc="0">Snowmobiles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Wisconsin</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is Wisconsin's oldest geocache. Located in Pike Lake State Park, hilly terrain, beautiful views. It's also the first cache placed in a Wisconsin State Park and the first placed with permission of WDNR park management.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;center&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td width="210" align="center"&gt;&lt;font size="-1"&gt;&lt;b&gt;This cache placed by a member of:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.wi-geocaching.com"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.wi-geocaching.com/banners/banner-large-border.gif" /&gt; &lt;font size="-2"&gt;(click to visit our website)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/center&gt;
9/23/02: Please note that climbing the hill from the road immediately to the east is forbidden by park rules, as posted on the signs. Please respect the rules so we stay on good terms with park managers. Access the cache by using established trails only.
&lt;p&gt;PLEASE -- If you search for this during the winter, do not walk on the ski trails when the snow is groomed for cross-country skiing. Use skis, or walk on the extreme edge of the trail so your footprints don't dig into the groomed snow. Also, no dogs are allowed on the state park trails during winter.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364685082"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T13:07:38</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4239968">MKisses</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">🥵 Phew. I’m glad it’s a cooler day today. We had to climb the tower before making this find. It’s mostly downhill from here. 🤗 TFTC!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364683495"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T13:01:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="50826398">aGuy252</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great scenery and amazing hike TFTC!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364894466"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="50826305">HHornet19</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Quite the hike today, but my little legs made it with a couple short breaks. TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364650419"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1569245">ninjashooter</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great Cache! Nice hike</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364269168"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="687627">Zorkmid</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Jatmo and I visited while heading home after Geowoodstock.  We signed the log GeoKW.  TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.5929" lon="-110.84885"><time>2001-06-09T00:00:00</time><name>GCBF4</name><desc>Teton Village (Jackson Hole's First) by DomainSquatter</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCBF4</url><urlname>Teton Village (Jackson Hole's First)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3060" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Teton Village (Jackson Hole's First)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>DomainSquatter</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="7797">DomainSquatter</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="0">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Wyoming</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Located high above Teton Village on the ski slopes directly under
the path of the tram. It is a couple of hundred yards below the
first tram tower near the top of the mountain. It is easy to find,
but requires a lot of hiking. Hiking and Mtn. Biking on the
roads/trails are open to the public. &lt;b&gt;This cache will probably
only be 'findable' in the warmer months of the year&lt;/b&gt;, when it's
not covered in snow.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This cache is located at about 7900 feet above sea level high above
Teton Village. It provides a great view of the Jackson Hole area.
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
The cache itself is a ziploc sandwich bag. It's initial contents
contain a pen and log book (compliments the Best Western's - The
Inn at Jackson Hole from the valley floor.), some chewing gum, a
small airplane, and a rock (as a weight).&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Once you have a found the area, the cache should be easy to locate.
It is just below he ski area's maintenance road directly underneath
the cables that pull the tram, a little bit south of one of the ski
lift loading areas. It is located near a wooden structure (see
picture).&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
If you decide to hike to it, you are in for quite a trek. There are
two ways to go. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
1) Ride the tram to the top and hike down. You can then either hike
back up to the top and ride the tram down or just hike back down to
the bottom.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
2) Follow the path of the tram, this is fairly steep you will go
from 6,300 feet to 7,900 in about 1.3 miles.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
3) Follow the maintenance road. This is about 3 miles, but
obviously not so steep. (If you go this way, watch for a
restaurant/lodge just above a ski lift, you need to make sure that
you follow the road that forks off (to the left if you are going
uphill) and goes just beneath this lodge.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
The road is &lt;b&gt;NOT open to drivers&lt;/b&gt;. Hikers and Mountain Bikers
are allowed.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
When I hid the cache, I took the 1.3 mile route up, but decided it
was too steep to take down, so I followed the road most of the way
down, using some of the ski slopes as occassional short-cuts. This
made for a 4.3 mile round trip.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
You may want to &lt;b&gt;look at the spoiler&lt;/b&gt; (encrypted), since it
will be a long way to come back if you have a hard time finding it!
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The cache is located in some granite rocks, just below the wooden structure.  (NOTE:  Only remains of the wodden structure are there still ... the main structure has been moved a bit, the pile of rocks is still there.)  It is in an area where two of the bigger rocks come together (down inside).  There are some smaller rocks piled on top of it to protect it and hide it.  However, some of the ziploc bag is exposed.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="245359754"><groundspeak:date>2012-06-29T18:20:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="531429">Heartland Cacher</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The cache and cache owner seemed to have moved on so this cache is being archived.  The Cache Owner can contact me ( HeartlandCacher@gmail.com ) if this is still a viable cache

Thanks

Heartland Cacher
Vol Cache Reviewer for Wyoming and Nebraska</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="244847735"><groundspeak:date>2012-06-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="424714">crcclu</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I am still going to look for it again before I make such requests. How do you know it cannot be found if you have not looked. Research shows that the tram has been moved. If you go look near the coords NOT under the tram lines. I would love to adopt this cache &amp; make sure it is maintained.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="244665911"><groundspeak:date>2012-06-25T21:58:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="764013">firion2.0</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Lemme see..

- Cache owner has not logged in since September of 2011.
- Cache last found nearly 5 years ago back in 2007.
- The last finder of the cache reported a cracked container with it being full of water.

The cache NEEDS MAINTENANCE.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="242955240"><groundspeak:date>2012-06-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="350523">bflentje</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Lemme see..

- Cache owner has not logged in since September of 2011.
- Cache last found nearly 5 years ago back in 2007.
- The last finder of the cache reported a cracked container with it being full of water.

The cache NEEDS MAINTENANCE.

Did the free pass to drive up the mountain go to your head or something??</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="242082396"><groundspeak:date>2012-06-15T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="424714">crcclu</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">RE: Anyone know how far down the mountain the cache is from where you disembark the tram? Tram is about 4100 vertical feet. About 1/3 way down &amp; you have to hike back up or all the way down. It is a serious hike! Please don't say it needs maintenance if you have not been there to look. Thank you!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="26.000867" lon="-81.620267"><time>2000-12-25T00:00:00</time><name>GCFA</name><desc>Christmas Cache by DOGBONE (adopted by anidanid, then Lorriebird)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCFA</url><urlname>Christmas Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="250" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Christmas Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>DOGBONE (adopted by anidanid, then Lorriebird)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Florida</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;Jingle Bells, Batman smells, Dogbone hid some stuff.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You may hike, or you may bike, it shouldn't be too ruff.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Of course to find, what's left behind, would be a great sensation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To begin, you must first check in at the ranger station.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Terrain rating: 2, Even little dogs could make this one&lt;br /&gt;
Overall difficulty: 2, When ya get there, bark like a mad dog&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ROCK ON!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;DOGBONE&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Admin Note: This is in Collier-Seminole State Park and there is a fee to enter. The trail is open between 8-5 DST and 8-4 STD time. Check in at the ranger station before attempting the cache. The ranger station is south east of the cache site along highway 41 at the entrance to the actual park at N25.59.516 W81.35.408. Please, use the mountain biking trail to approach the cache at N25.59.917 W81.35.918. The trail can be wet at times and the mosquitoes can be brutal certain times of the year. The hike is around 3 miles round trip, and the final container is about 100 feet off the trail. You cannot access this cache without trespassing on private property unless you use the designated trail. Please do not endanger the future of Florida's oldest cache by disregarding this critical rule.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The owner of this cache is long gone and anidanid tirelessly took care of this cache after she adopted it in 2004. Then in 2013 she gave Lorriebird a most excellent birthday present and allowed her to adopt it!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="background-color:#2ecc71;"&gt;Owners Note December 25th 2020:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; Happy 20th Birthday, Christmas Cache! The oldest cache in Florida turned 20 years old today! This milestone birthday was celebrated with an event, a cake, and then a hike. Here's to the next 20 years!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/gs-geo-images/436d727b-0c47-46e0-bb2d-fda04dcddd5f_l.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364100497"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2551708">stkafz</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yeah! I'made it! Means I survived the mosquitoes!!! Another oldest state Cache in my file. Saw an alligator on my way there. At the coordinates it was a quick grab. Thanks for placing and maintaining this one for so long!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362745475"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1950402">KIAX</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wow
Took time to hike in.
But having it as a smile on a map, worst all trouble
Tfth</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362689912"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1135498">Suse&amp;HRo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Since our road trip also took us to Naples, this Grandpa Cache was naturally on our bucket list. We read some old log entries and decided we really needed mosquito face nets. They were sold out at Walmart, so we had to make a detour to Ace Hardware. We picked up our tickets from the park ranger, sprayed ourselves generously with bug spray, pulled the mosquito nets over our heads, and set off. In the end, it wasn't as bad as we'd expected, but we definitely wouldn't have wanted to do without the mosquito nets. We found the cache without any trouble and retrieved a travel bug.
Thank you for keeping this old cache going. 💙</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362506727"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="12983729">Goofygrams</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I drove with lynnray to Naples from the Orlando area for some counties &amp; the oldest for lynnray &amp; some other targeted caches for me!  I needed lynnray to find this guy, an oldest state prize!  I was here in 8/2019 &amp; logged a bad experience…too much water!  I was here in 12/2019 &amp; had a great experience finding this prize!  This time it was good, except for the mosquitoes🦟 which were ferocious, but we were prepared for them!  I’m visiting my TBs today! Thanx for being a part of another great geoAdventure, lorriebird!  Have a Magical Caching Day! 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362062921"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5284151">lynnray</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">What an adventure. I came down to Naples for some caching fun, with a few targeted caches, the Christmas Cache being the main target.we heard about how bad the mosquitos were here already, so we went to Walmart and purchased some bug spray and mosquito nets. Now we are ready, let me tell you, I am SO glad we invested in the nets. The mosquitos were hungry and out in force. From the time we got out of our car, there was a constant buzz all the way to the cache. We found it with no problem, secure in place, I took the traveler that was resting there and left on in exchange. I hope someone picks it up soo to further its travels. Goofygrams had found it before so she brought me down by the goodness of her heart. Thank you for keeping this cache alive long enough for me to find it.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="38.88976666666667" lon="-77.00985"><time>2001-06-27T00:00:00</time><name>GCDE1</name><desc>Capitol View by Buddhavista</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCDE1</url><urlname>Capitol View</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3553" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Capitol View</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Buddhavista</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1683">buddhavista</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>District of Columbia</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is a Virtual Cache (there is no cache container).  It marks my favorite view of Washington D.C.

Note: Since 9-11, the terrace has been barricaded off.  You can get close to the coordinates, but you may not be able to get to the exact location.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>If you are a resident or planning to visit the city, this is a must see spot.  This is a historic location where the inaugural podium is placed.  The spot marks the place that many of our Presidents were sworn into office.  Be sure to bring your camera for this fantastic view of the city.
&lt;p&gt;
Log your visit and let me know of other great spots in DC.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364908559"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6665740">Otgonsurenb</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC. Greetings from Mongolia</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364464203"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T17:03:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="45076644">Sob2250</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTV!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364659048"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13067786">hiverdeinvierno</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">My mother and I are currently on a tour by coach from the East Coast to the West Coast.
After the city tour, we still had a few hours of free time and could, for instance, visit one of the nearby museums. But Mom and I, of course, absolutely wanted to get even closer to the Capitol!
So far in Washington, the things that have impressed me most are the geocaches GC2657 and GC25E1; they moved me to tears, even amidst the hustle and bustle and the crowds of tourists during the day. For that, I didn't even need the silence of the night—which makes one even more contemplative regarding the terrible experiences of those poor soldiers!
A colleague gave me the little turtle—along with a cookie inscribed with "Favorite Colleague"—before I left, so it definitely had to make it into the photo :)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364170163"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T09:03:33</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="52719610">TeamLegendary_</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Such a fun cache! Got this one on day 2 of my tour to NY and DC!!!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364118366"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T00:23:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1810758">ReidRick</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice night to check out the capital. It is quite magnificent being so close to it </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="440486099"><groundspeak:date>2014-08-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Been here a few times in my life but this time to get a smiley on the way to dinner.   Thanks for the virtual! 

This filled a Jasmer month,  oldest cache in DC, and was my 1,700th find. 

Awesome!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.134983" lon="-73.5504"><time>2000-12-11T00:00:00</time><name>GCE4</name><desc>Another Brick in the Wall by the GeoFerret</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCE4</url><urlname>Another Brick in the Wall</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="228" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Another Brick in the Wall</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>the GeoFerret</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="272">Nona</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Connecticut</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Container: Army Surplus Munitions Box&lt;br /&gt;
Difficulty: 2&lt;br /&gt;
Terrain: 2</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The stash container is one of those Army Surplus Munitions Boxes.
Its the smaller sized one, about 5" x 10" x 12". It should be water
tight, but just in case, I put each of the goodies in a zip lock. 
&lt;p&gt;Its a public park with a trail system, but as I just found out,
there is a charge to enter the park (Seasonal, summer only, $6 per
person, see &lt;b&gt;Additional Hints&lt;/b&gt;) Nice area. It's close to a
wooden bridge over a nearby river. The trail system has these
numbered pillars on it. Look for number 8, then follow the stone
wall off the trail into the woods. Follow it back for about 50
yards to where another wall meets up with it from the left. Its
hidden in the adjoining wall about 3' from where they connect.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you have time while you're there, take a hike through the
trail loop in the park. There's a great elevated walk through the
middle of the marsh, well worth it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The GeoFerret&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>To avoid the park fee, I used to park at the end of Hannahs Rd. and walk in through there. It's been a while, but I believe the trails are still accessible that way.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363623132"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T18:02:57</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54971536">CBurrellkids</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">That was fun!  - one of our favorites so far! Great job. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363117232"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5445477">Albus_Birch</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Figured out parking ahead of time. Parked and made short hike to this oldie. Looked around a bit before my wife read the hint and then we both saw from a distance.

Thanks for keeping this oldie going!

8028</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363011987"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="11872615">btwillbethere</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dropped by after an event with DredgenIrati. First oldest state cache for me. Tftc! :)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362835615"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8724011">Candy Apple 68</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from Letchworth State Park in Mount Morris, NY! :) FP from me.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362862531"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T10:05:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54239439">DredgenIrati</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">my first oldest! tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="45.299633" lon="-122.081417"><time>2000-05-12T00:00:00</time><name>GC12</name><desc>GC12 5/12/2000 by Jerry Connelly (GeoNap &amp; fractal &amp; lobotomy)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC12</url><urlname>GC12 5/12/2000</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="18" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>GC12 5/12/2000</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Jerry Connelly (GeoNap &amp; fractal &amp; lobotomy)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="204578">lobotomy</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Oregon</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>near Brightwood, OR. White and blue bucket
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>From US 26,  go to Southwest Firwood Road. Take a left on Southeast Wildcat Mountain Drive. Continue to GC15V8K . From there, take the next right and look for a closed off road on your right. You will have to park there and walk.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364480384"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T16:29:58</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25803823">grtcornholio</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I’ve been wanting to get this crown jewel for quite some time and I spent my Saturday hiking the trails.  This one coming back is definitely harder than getting there, but I feel blessed to live in the great NW where geocaching started.  </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364497441"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T09:31:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3330050">Stephi_Dita</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I’m currently in Oregon for work. Naturally, when you have the opportunity to be here, you also keep an eye out for some great caches. In this state, it doesn’t take long to find them.

So, early in the morning, I grabbed my rental car and drove from Portland to this historic geocaching location.

It took me a little while to find the correct starting point. With almost no cell service in the area, navigating to the right trail wasn’t particularly easy. Once I arrived, I had to search for a bit before the well-hidden container finally revealed itself.

I was thrilled to find this old cache and feel fortunate to have had the opportunity to visit it. Thanks for preserving this piece of geocaching history!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363434841"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T04:31:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2761157">Memfis Mafia</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">
Thanks lobotomy for placing this 1.0/ 2.5 Traditional in Oregon, United States. Always cool to see what folks are hiding out there!

Log Notes:

Sometimes the best geocaching weekends are not the ones where you pile up giant numbers…they are the ones that remind you why you started caching in the first place.

This weekend was one of those.

The original mission was simple enough. I needed to track down two specific old geocaches for the Quad Jasmer Challenge which I will be able to complete on the Worldwide Cache Cruise this summer. The targets were GC12 and GC17, and if things went well I hoped to add a little bonus history with GC16 — ‘Another Oldie.’

Mission accomplished.

But honestly…the caches were only part of the story.

Somewhere between the trails, the quiet woods, and the miles on the foot, I found myself slowing down in a way I have not done in a long time. No rushing. No noise. Just the rhythm of moving through nature and hunting pieces of geocaching history that have somehow survived for more than two decades.

That is the part that hit me.

These old caches are more than containers. They are time capsules from another era of the game. You can feel the care that went into hiding them, and you can feel the dedication of the people who kept them alive all these years. Twenty-plus years of maintenance, repairs, logbooks, weather, floods, storms, and changing technology…and they are still out there waiting for the next cacher.

There is something grounding about that.

The hikes reminded me that most of the stress we carry around every day is temporary. Out there in the woods, chasing old geocaches and forgotten trails, life gets very small in the best possible way.

This weekend reminded me exactly why I fell in love with geocaching in the first place.

This is geocaching.







Who we are:
As of , we’ve found about  caches and hidden . We’re not chasing numbers this year—we’re chasing **GeoDates**, good logs, and even better stories.

We host the [Geocache Talk Podcast](https://geocachetalk.com), where we talk all things caching—and have been fortunate enough to be able to give back a little through the creation of Cache Odyssey, Worldwide Cache Fest, Worldwide Cache Cruise, and the Podcast of Hope.

If you like geocaching books:  
📘 [Geocaching in the Age of AI](https://www.amazon.com/Geocaching-Age-AI-Adventures-Community-ebook/dp/B0FF7F2RZ7?ref_=ast_author_dp_aw&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.heixkHe126vLv9NfU4a7qMcr9kyt0JwCYa2XqGKVq6a-QDItwCR5WzRQ2qxe_pd-b3VtAAMzgTRKCazETCgJY8kRQ9IUAySsML1jFWP4Dcy8MeWl43oeY7z5EMPxE9tr.T3EBaZ6V4gKLZ7UXDODqrvOl2EWERF79bnjdAyWCZgM&amp;dib_tag=AUTHOR)  
📗[Geocaching Challenges](https://www.amazon.com/Geocaching-Challenges-Game-Within-ebook/dp/B07Y7LTTS1?ref_=ast_author_dp_aw&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.heixkHe126vLv9NfU4a7qMcr9kyt0JwCYa2XqGKVq6a-QDItwCR5WzRQ2qxe_pd-b3VtAAMzgTRKCazETCgJY8kRQ9IUAySsML1jFWP4Dcy8MeWl43oeY7z5EMPxE9tr.T3EBaZ6V4gKLZ7UXDODqrvOl2EWERF79bnjdAyWCZgM&amp;dib_tag=AUTHOR)


Or:
🌍 our EarthCaches (just search under “Memfis Mafia”—they’re out there and hopefully both accessible and educational-ish!) 

**Conditions Report**  
General Status: In good shape.  
Log Status: Signed/answers sent.  

🔁 Keep enjoying the game—and make it better than you found it.

—Memfis Mafia






</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363363216"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5889280">Checkers042</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It is done! I Finally made it out here for the coveted GC12 Smiley!!! Such a fun hike through beautiful country; I'm sure I will be back! Special thanks to everyone who helps maintain this cache and these trails. Tftc!!!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363245066"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T10:12:57</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="50822126">Alwina0</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Spotted during a tour through 11 states in the Western US, together with Team VLNL (ErwinKarin, Inge-de-Mol, TeamSannie, Marcske57, and Alwina0). TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1120654993"><groundspeak:date>2022-08-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I know to avoid the national forest during hunting season but was surprised today by the number of groups doing recreational target practice.  This is their forest too. 

We had initially driven past the trail head and as we did, I noted that there was a car of people unloading gear, including targets.  I thought it was interesting but didn't think more of it until we realized our error and were back at the trailhead.

We spent about 20 minutes talking with the shooters and some other geocaching groups.  We ultimately decided to pass on this one one this day at this time.   

This was just bad luck of our timing.  I'm glad so many others managed to get out there before us or maybe after.

The group of shooters we talked with were very friendly and open about what they were doing and how they could accommodate our presence but we all agreed that the other groups that did not know we were there could be a concern. They seemed well trained and handled themselves and their firearms appropriately.

I left disappointed, but pleased it was such a positive encounter.

I will no doubt be back!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="46.03535" lon="-111.420883"><time>2001-03-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC492</name><desc>Fairweather by Don and Nancy Wilson</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC492</url><urlname>Fairweather</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1170" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Fairweather</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Don and Nancy Wilson</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="50069939">pospilgramage</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Not chosen</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Montana</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>year round accessability, easy to get to along the banks of the
Missouri River</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>On your drive to this cache enjoy a beutiful view of a remote spot
in Montana. It will take about 1 hr to make the drive in and 1 hour
to make the drive out. You can add this the amount of time it takes
you to find the cache. The cache is a ammo can located at the base
of a three trunked tree. After visiting the cache, carefully rehide
it as the area is frequented by fishermen and campers. Happy
hunting in Montana. As of 4/27/07, the owners have obtained a
Montana Fish Wildlife and Parks two year permit for this cache at
this site. Remember Cache in , trash out. Help keep this busy
fishing access clean.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The tree can be pinpointed by the intersection of two compass bearings.  Sight 187 deg magnetic to a prominate and isolated dead tree with a broken off top. Triangulate the previous bearing with a bearing of 102 deg magnetic to an isolated dead cottonwood with two trunks.
</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364907564"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47911">medicineman</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Was dubious about the last 1.5 miles but the end was a pleasant place to have lunch. AND, the purpose of our stop was, of course, to score the oldest in Montana. Easy follow the geotrail. Signed the log and left a path tag. Favorite awarded, of course</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363941082"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T14:01:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8814283">TheLF</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Continuing my Odyssey quest after GeoWoodstock in Hutchinson, KS. I may get home on 3 weeks, and then again, I may not. I’m a geocacher and retired.😎.
**********
I was on my way to Helena, and I noticed how close I was to this old, so of course I changed my route and made the drive out here. Really nice location and everything is fine with the cache . 
Thanks for the smiley and thanks for maintaining this all these years. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363906841"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1454863">Paintedwarrior</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Enjoyed a scenic drive from Yellowstone this morning and had fun finding this oldie. Coords are good and it’s a beautiful spot. TFTC. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363909271"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T11:44:15</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4051795">quadguy47</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">caching with dukemartin and paintedwarrior. great location. fantastic drive to gz. enjoyed the river. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363908543"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T11:39:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="887579">dukemartin</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it with Paintedwarrior and quadguy47.  Thanks for the cache.  </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="35.3365" lon="-106.476833"><time>2001-02-02T00:00:00</time><name>GC191</name><desc>Open Space  7 by Jim Dick, Jr. (adopted by tealeaf &amp; SpacePanda89)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC191</url><urlname>Open Space  7</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="401" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Open Space  7</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Jim Dick, Jr. (adopted by tealeaf &amp; SpacePanda89)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="44528694">SpacePanda89</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>New Mexico</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>It was in a rock cairn, which is now just a ring of rocks. Someone needed the ammo box more than we did. Lucky number seven, you can drive, if they’d let you, right to it. Three posts are at 290 deg magnetic. A dead topped tree is at 116 deg magnetic and seven paces away, hurry it could be all the way dead, by the time you find it. There is a nice view however, especially on a cool crisp day.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Park at N35 19.71, W106 28.57
&lt;p&gt;To claim this cache, take a picture of yourself (or your GPSr if you are solo), at the ring of rocks.&lt;/p&gt;
tealeaf here For those seeking the oldest active caches in New Mexico, the history is a bit murky. They were all placed as letterboxes in 1998 before geocaching was a reality. Jim Dick taught GPS classes at REI and converted some of the caches as geocaching came into being. The actual order of placement is questionable and the lowest GC number is not the earliest hide by date and 7a and 7b seem to have been placed before 6 and 7. These were placed before the reviewer name and publication date were on caches. The earliest log date is 1/28/2001 on 7a. Mouser, the first finder, did not mention the other 3 that were first logged on 2/3, so it is likely that they had not been published yet as they are all in the same area and he would not have skipped them. 7,7b and 6 are all logged for the first time on 2/3/2001. Jim likely never thought these would become historical records and he was never an active cacher. Open Space letterbox 6 (archived) by Jim Dick, jr. adopted by Team Tuxawuxa | GC190 | 04/15/2001 Open Space letterbox 7b (archived) by Jim Dick, Jr. adopted by Team Tuxawuxa | GC193 | 01/15/2001 Open Space Letterbox 7A, ( archived)1/4 section corner by Jim Dick, Jr. adopted by Team Tuxawuxa | GC192 |01/15/2001
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364109976"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T18:51:59</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5221874">iceberrrrg</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with MuggleMomma on a trip to Kansas and Colorado another oldie in the books. Nice hike out to this one. Thanks for placing this Cache!! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364112262"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T17:32:04</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="33528440">MuggleMomma</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a road trip with iceberrrrg from northern Minnesota to Geowoodstock XXll then off to CO, NM and back to MN. 
This was one of our main destinations today. We went to the Capulin Volcano first, then off to grab the oldest here.  It was about 1.5 miles RT grabbing a trad and LB along the way.  This makes #33 of the lower 48 oldest caches in each state. Thanks for placing this virtual cache and for adding to the fun!  </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363908202"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6565197">RFF-Reid Family</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Sorry about the original log. I thought I was drafting. I was a little concerned about getting this one. We've had a lot of misadventures on this road trip so I was reluctant to take even a short hike in the desert. Mr. RFF still wanted to get this one so we did! I'm really glad we did it, no mishaps on the hike, thank goodness! This is out 10th state's oldest cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363509074"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="928892">Sir Dave</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yay!.
Another state's oldest knocked out.
Thanks for keeping this one going for so long.
Sir Dave 
Barboursville, WV
May 25, 2026 9:17 AM</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363509455"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T09:19:18</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7067857">kirklking</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The destination for our hike.  Logging an oldie  TFTV</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="53.53745" lon="-112.983733"><time>2000-11-04T00:00:00</time><name>GCA6</name><desc>Strathcona Wilderness 1 by Michael Houle</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCA6</url><urlname>Strathcona Wilderness 1</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="166" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Strathcona Wilderness 1</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Michael Houle</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1876">scummy-boots</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="0">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="0">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="0">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="1">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="0">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="64" inc="0">Tree climbing required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Alberta</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;p&gt;This is the first geocache placed in Alberta (2nd in Canada) and has an interesting history. Read the first 4 log entries for more information.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Notes:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;No dogs allowed in the wilderness area&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For winter time access, please don't walk on the cross-country ski tracks.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;For more information about the Strathcona Wilderness area including hours of operation (the gate gets locked at 4:30 most days), see &lt;a href="="&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;. From the lodge, it is a 15-20 minute walk to the cache area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;You can take wildlife trails right to the location.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Good Luck and wear sturdy footwear.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363336482"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53354">gpcomd</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I had already found this one back in June of 2014, but geowydow needed this one for another oldest province cache.  
Perfect day to be on the trails - sunny, warm, a little breeze, dry ground and not a mosquito in sight.  
Thanks for keeping this ancient cache alive  and adding to the days adventures 😀😀
Stopped off two travelers I have been dragging around for a while.  
GPC &amp; GW, Orleans</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363251888"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3228617">Geowydow</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">West Canada travels Part 2 with GPC.
This was the target cache for today. Found easily after the hike. Beautiful trails throughout! 
I dropped off 2 TBs, GPC dropped off 1.
TFTC,
Geowydow and GPComd
Orléans</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363458410"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4067764">Géochum</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I found it with Tatie.
Thank you for the nice cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362928096"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T11:48:58</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="833553">tatie</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Together with Geochum, we continue our journey westward. We take the opportunity to find a few caches here and there along the way. 
Thanks for keeping this old cache alive.
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361235745"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T15:38:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="33518942">Zippy18</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tftc ver cool this one was on our radar thanks </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="49.2753" lon="-123.232967"><time>2001-02-02T00:00:00</time><name>GC1DD</name><desc>Treehugger (BC's First Cache) by QuigleyJones (original owners Todd &amp; Chikako)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1DD</url><urlname>Treehugger (BC's First Cache)</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="477" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Treehugger (BC's First Cache)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>QuigleyJones (original owners Todd &amp; Chikako)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="340466">QuigleyJones</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="37" inc="0">Horses</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="64" inc="0">Tree climbing required</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>British Columbia</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>From parking area, it is only about a 15 - 20 minute walk, with an initial steep 50 - 60 metre elevation change. The actual cache will be off the main trail by approximately 20 - 30 metres.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.groundspeak.com/cache/99bd8e36-bb6b-4f9d-91f1-4eec3dbcefd7.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
This is the oldest cache location in British Columbia. It's been here since Feb 2001. Because of the original owners having left the hobby, this cache has been adopted by QuigleyJones, formerly dogbreathcanada. Thanks to Groundspeak for allowing and facilitating the adoption when there was no mechanism in place as there is now.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Cache is a &lt;strike&gt;blue 1.5L&lt;/strike&gt; camo 9L container.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
To reduce environmental impact, the cache is hidden between a mound and fern next to lonely evergreen, covered with bits of rotting log and bark. If coming from Marine Drive, when you're about 25 metres from the cache location (or if coming from the other direction, when you're 25 metres past the cache location), you'll see a fairly well-trodden side trail. It has a log across it and pink 'GMT' flagging tape hanging from an adjacent branch. Keep to that trail, to ensure that no further trails are created. That trail will bring you straight to the cache location.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font color="red"&gt;GVRD Parks personnel have been visiting the cache from time to time, presumably to check on the environmental impact. Here is the most recent note left in the logbook by the GVRD:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;i&gt;GVRD PARKS check-up on cache. Remember to obey all park rules when visiting. Be respectful of vegetation while off trail. Try not to be seen if going off trail so others won't follow.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Please stay on the main trail until you see pink flagging tape. There is also pink flagging tape on the branch above the cache. If you're visiting the site, be careful, as GVRD Parks monitoring of this cache could affect future geocaching policies in the GVRD parks system.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;!-- BCGA Info Block Begin --&gt;
&lt;table width="80%" border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#669966" align="center"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="middle"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.bcgeocaching.com/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.bcgeocaching.com/images/roundlogo-green5.gif" border="0" width="72" height="72" alt="BCGA" title="BCGA" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;font face="verdana" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"&gt;If you are a Geocacher in the province of British Columbia, please join the &lt;b&gt;British Columbia Geocaching Association&lt;/b&gt;. The BCGA is your portal to caching in and around BC. Visit &lt;a href="http://www.bcgeocaching.com/" target="_blank"&gt;bcgeocaching.com&lt;/a&gt; for details!&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;!-- BCGA Info Block End --&gt;&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>pink flagging tape</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364889810"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T13:10:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10334296">InfamousPanda</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Together with Pepacaches, we’re embarking on an unforgettable journey across continents. From Amsterdam, we take to the skies, crossing the ocean with a stopover in Iceland before touching down in Vancouver—where our adventure truly begins.    
    
Drawn by the call of the road, we head south to Seattle to visit the legendary APE cache and HQ. Soon after, we cross back into Canada, pick up our camper, and set off into the wild—where the real expedition begins.    
    
Our path winds through the breathtaking landscapes of Hope, Kelowna, Banff, and Jasper, and far beyond, all the way to the rugged frontiers of Whitehorse. Towering mountains, endless forests, and remote wilderness guide our way as we travel through both iconic destinations and hidden gems few ever see.    
    
Driven by curiosity and the thrill of the hunt, we search for caches in the most extraordinary places, each one a small treasure marking our journey. Every stop reveals something new—epic views, unexpected discoveries, and stories we’ll carry with us long after the road ends.    
    
This is one of the caches we uncovered along the way.    
    
    
    
QuigleyJones Bedankt voor het leggen en onderhouden van de cache Treehugger (BC's First Cache).  
Gevonden op 1 jun 2026 om 13:10. Dit was cache 24.096.  
  
Het weer tijdens het cachen 🌥️ Bewolkt  🌡️22°C  💧47%  🌬️4 m/s    
  
    </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364889362"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T13:07:29</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4531772">PePacaches</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it, on the way from Vancouver and Seattle to Whitehorse, together with Infamous Panda. We are going to look for as many caches as possible and this is one of them.

Thanks for placing and maintaining this cache.

Kind regards from PePacaches, Tiel, from The Netherlands.
Infamous Panda sent the answers for the earthcaches. 

Gevonden, op weg van Vancouver en Seattle naar Whitehorse, samen met Infamous Panda. We gaan zoveel mogelijk caches vinden en dit is er een van.
Infamous Panda zend alle antwoorden van alle earthcaches. 

Bedankt voor het plaatsen en onderhouden van deze cache.

Vriendelijke groeten van PePacaches, Tiel, Nederland.
13:07
1 jun 2026</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364473275"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T15:14:54</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26410123">Themojofamily</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yay! I’m so happy to have found BC’s oldest cache. I’ve wanted this many times while in the big city but have never had the extra time to make it happen.
Today I put extra time into the scheduled trip and dragged some muggle friends with us. It took us 30min total from car to car (parking at Spanish Banks) with one other bonus cache en route.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364467526"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3011698">C_C_C</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Road Trippin with my Dad Ragfoot. It was really nice when we finally found it. Beautiful area! TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364467441"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2704859">Ragfoot</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">@ 2:05 PM 
Day 12 road trip from San Diego with my daughter C_C_C. This was not an easy find. Even with some excellent hints in previous logs, it took half an hour before my daughter spotted the tape hanging about head high.
SL, TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="796712315"><groundspeak:date>2018-08-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Got done a little earlier than expected at a client site. There was no way I could make it back to the hotel to change and then do this find before heading to the airport... 

So I fired up Google maps and it said to get on the 44 bus at 'Bay 5' in 3 minutes.  Prefect.... Just where exactly is bay 5 please?  So I guess I mad this a multi of a sorts...  

directly there from downtown.  Well... Direct might not be exactly right.   The bus got me a few KM from the cache... So down the hill I went, past the friendly work crew repairing the path.  I discreetly changed from my work shirt to a polo shirt along the way... Then along the beach.  There is nothing quite like walking along a beach in dress shoes!  I got to the trail head and immediately started up.  No kidding the initial part is a bit of a climb!  It was exactly 692 stairs up!  (maybe not exactly.)

Nice walk along the ridge and I was quickly heading down the side trail and soon found an obvious GZ area but the GPS was pointing further on... I followed a bit but soon returned to the obvious area and low and behold...  
~~~
Drat.  Urgent Email.  ARGH.... just a moment, while I whip out the laptop and do a bit of work...  ok, that wasn't so bad...  now where was I??
~~~
and low and behold there was a very old regular sized geocache!  Sweet!

I made quick work of signing the log and was soon on my way back down the stairs.  Humm, funny, this time, it was only exactly 175 steps.  (exactly.)   Funny that.  Stopped for a quick bite at before tackling the long climb back up to the bus stop.


Thanks for a awesome adventure and for keeping this oldy alive and active.  Photos attached should provide a chuckle.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="49.17375" lon="-99.661783"><time>2001-02-05T00:00:00</time><name>GC21C</name><desc>C1BUA - cache 1n a builtup area by Brian Drader</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC21C</url><urlname>C1BUA - cache 1n a builtup area</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="540" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>C1BUA - cache 1n a builtup area</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Brian Drader</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="3188">e8ght</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Manitoba</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This 1st geocache in Manitoba used to be in Winnipeg but has now been moved to the indicated coordinates in Killarney MB.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The container is a blue and white Coleman jug. Please fasten the lid snugly to protect the contents.
&lt;p&gt;Please leave:&lt;br /&gt;
-the cache container (Coleman jug)&lt;br /&gt;
-a writing instrument&lt;br /&gt;
-the logbook&lt;br /&gt;
Everything else in the cache container is fair game.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Take something, leave something of equal value.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Feel free to drop larger goodies into the mailbox if you can't fit them inside the cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Good hunting!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cheers,&lt;br /&gt;
Brian&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Near corner of garage</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1362992714"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T16:21:38</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53705791">GeoGinnyYukon</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you. Great TB hotel 🙂 grabbed TB CB0WKK</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361257173"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T22:13:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1756044">1purplemonkeydishwasher1</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello from Winnipeg. We are spending the long weekend caching in the international peace gardens and Brandon hills area. This cache I had to stop for. Thabks for keeping this old cache alive. Great to see the old logbook still in the cache. Added a favorite and grabbed a TB</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361178736"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T12:37:10</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="20859057">_TheBoz_</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 3 of the Team BS 2026 road trip!  We flew into Winnipeg on Wednesday evening, TheBoz from NS and StonesFanInTO from Toronto. 
Today we are travelling from Morden, MB to Dickinson, ND.  
This was our first stop of the day, and of course a nice quick find :). Thanks so much for keeping this one going!!  

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361200134"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T10:42:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22496111">StonesFanInTO</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">2026 The Boz &amp; StonesFanInTO Roadtrip!!!

Day 3: Morden, Manitoba to Dickenson, ND

Started day with Manitoba’s oldest and then off the North Dakota.

Definitely in a built up area and a very quick find!  Happy to add another oldest cache in a province to my list!

TFTC 
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357845719"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-28T17:03:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2531636">Team-Gates</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 4 of the Cool Crew Spring Trip. Fun cache, stamped with Cool Crew. Thanks!

Oldest in Manitoba!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="47.988467" lon="-66.870067"><time>2001-04-21T00:00:00</time><name>GC760</name><desc>Beginners Luck?  First Geocache in New Brunswick ! by Insp Gadget</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC760</url><urlname>Beginners Luck?  First Geocache in New Brunswick !</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1888" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Beginners Luck?  First Geocache in New Brunswick !</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Insp Gadget</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="7503">Insp Gadget</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>New Brunswick</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Shouldn't be very hard to find. My first Geocache and just making
sure I'm doing everything right. Located not far off the
road.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The container an ammo can. Inside there is a log, pen, pencil, and
some trading items.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Park on Flatlands Rd, next to the small church. The cache is located on the side of the road opposite the church behind some trees.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1360643498"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-12T19:12:31</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="55333990">Erica2604</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1337308919"><groundspeak:date>2025-12-08T17:55:10</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53682134">CLParadis</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you for the find. 
Cache is good condition. 
Day 8 of my adventures 30 CACHES IN 30 DAYS, for completing 
COAP 2025. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1334424360"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-13T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="79207">kootenay pirates</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Mr. Pirate created a video of our ["Cross Canada Geocaching Adventure" with Granitic Intrusions](https://youtu.be/QlX-mAhgc8g?si=AtEOdHzBPOrNLaBZ) that we would like to share. 
Kootenay Pirates ☠️ ☠️</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1333041408"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7493687">Poupou29</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**«ENNNNNNNFIN!!!! je l'ai eue la tabar...(bip)»** 😂

Oui, Oui.... c’est exactement ce que j’ai crié en la trouvant 😁

Ça fait des années que je l'avais dans le collimateur celle-là! 
La plus vieille cache du Nouveau-Brunswick, c'est pas rien

En 2025, je m'étais donnée comme mission de v'nir y gribouiller le journal des visiteurs.

Mission Accomplie: Check ✅... c'est maintenant fait! YAY! 🤘

Quelle année de roadtrips, une tournée avec beaucoup de caches vintages si je peux dire 😅

Me seront passées entre les mains une belle brochette de veilles caches dont celles de:

- L'ile du Prince Edouard
- Nouvelle-Ecosse et Canada par le fait même
- Connecticut
- Massachusetts
- New Jersey
- New Hampshire
- Maine
- New York


Attention: l'année 2025 n'est pas terminée! 😀

Si tout va bien, je compte bien aller dire coucou à la plus vieille de la Floride en décembre.. en tout cas, on verra bien.

Merci Insp Gadget de la maintenir en vie encore longtemps

Poupou29 la québécoise qui a déjà signé la plus vieille du Québec en 2024





</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1331156119"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-22T11:15:06</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="11683508">Richbou</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Jour deux de notre road trip , le tour de la Gaspésie avec mon amie Poupou29 . 
Grosse journée de géocaching et beaucoup de kilomètres .
Notre liste de caches est bien garnies , et bien sur on en découvre d'autre avec une belle cotte sur notre parcourt . On as même fait des caches dans un sentier de 4 roues ! l'auto as quatre roues ?
C'est aujourd'hui , on vas signer la plus vielle cache au Nouveau Brunswick 😛
Un rêve de quatre ans que vas réaliser Poupou29 😁
Enfin je l'ai signer la Tabarnac ! me disait avec un grand sourire  Poupou29 
Elle écrit à son chum pour lui annoncé la bonne nouvelle !
Il lui répond ! enfin ! je vais avoir la paix avec cette cache là !
On est pouffer de rire tout les deux dans l'auto 😁
Direction la Gaspésie  , on continue à signer d'autre caches .
Merci  Insp Gadget pour cette cache  1PF</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="47.617833" lon="-52.654333"><time>2001-06-30T00:00:00</time><name>GCE1C</name><desc>The Lookout: first ever cache in Newfoundland by Roger Green, Zachary, Alastair, Andrew, Elizabeth</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCE1C</url><urlname>The Lookout: first ever cache in Newfoundland</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3612" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>The Lookout: first ever cache in Newfoundland</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Roger Green, Zachary, Alastair, Andrew, Elizabeth</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="8731">geneman</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="0">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="0">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="0">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="0">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="0">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Newfoundland and Labrador</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Adjacent to East Coast Trail, approx 1 km SE of--and 150m higher than--the Logy Bay Ocean Sciences Centre.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;The cache was originally hidden in the prominent stone-lined pit 20 to 40 m SW of the highest point in the area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In 2001, this area was relatively unknown and rarely visited. With the growth of the East Coast Trail, this has changed, so that it is now quite a busy spot on a fine day. Such is the nature of 'progress'.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;From the Lookout you can see a bald eagle's nest on the cliffs to the south (bring binoculars).&lt;/p&gt;
-----------------------------------------------------------
&lt;p&gt;UPDATE Aug-06-2006: The cache has been refurbished. In the bottom of the pit you will now find NOTHING! The previous cache container was stolen :-( . Since the pit is too obvious a place--and prone to discovery by a casual hiker--I have hidden the new container some distance away. It is now on the ground in the middle of a small but prominent clump of trees. From the pit the container is 47m distant, on a bearing of 302 deg true. The coords of the container are 47°37.07' N, 52°39.26' W.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;-----------------------------------------------------------&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;May be approached:&lt;br /&gt;
(a) starting from the parking lot of the Ocean Sciences Centre and climbing the hill to the South.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;or (b) Along the East Coast Trail starting at Quidi Vidi or the DFO building and going North.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;View photos and log book entries from 2001 at: http://home.thezone.net/~rgreen/geocache.htm&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364737619"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T11:15:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8279665">QuiltinAnnie</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We arrived in St John’s very early this morning, and as we weren’t able to get into our accommodation until 3pm, we thought we should spend the waiting time by going on a hike and finding some caches!! So after a delicious brekkie at Cora’s, we headed over to walk a bit of the Sugarloaf Parh. Specially to find the oldest cache in Newfoundland!!!  Parked in the parking lot and headed up the trail!! It was cold (6C), foggy and windy. We left 30+C temps at home. But we had our toques and mitts, and off we went. We also were wearing our heavy duty hiking boots, and were we ever glad we made this hike wearing that footwear. That trail is amazing, but tough. The views were spectacular!! Definitely worthwhile!!!  Wild!!!  A quick find at the posted coordinates! This was the goal of the day and we found it!!!

Thank you geneman for the The Lookout: first ever cache in Newfoundland Traditional 

# 14146, in Newfoundland and Labrador, Canada
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363019117"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T18:17:17</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2174069">Paul n Susan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This was our goal for today, but you would never know it.  We parked the car and had a chat with a lady who was sitting in here truck while hubby was on the trails.  'Are ya goin to see the iceberg' she says, no we're not.  Anyway, the entire there and back, which was a fun challenge in itself, we were met with icy conversation, only a half-mile from here, how far?, did you see it? on and on.

Imagine our surprise that said iceberg was only 60 metres or so from NL's first ever geocache.  Who knew?  We signed in and hauled the cache to take a proper beauty shot then we brought it back to where it belonged and began the beautiful trip back to the parking lot.

Our ideals for this trip included seeing an iceberg (mission accomplished) and finding this cache (ditto).  Off to see puffins next week.  Do you know of any caches that are 60 metres away from whales?</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361972668"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T13:02:44</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54088980">J1ggsDinner</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice one! Tftc! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358942979"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6887855">JREnarson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for the cache. Giving this significant cache a favorite point, both for how old it is and for the enjoyable hike to get there.  We dropped off 3 TBs in the cache for the next cachers to hopefully grab.

J was in the area for a weeklong work trip.  But since the work part of the trip didn't start until Monday, he had a bit of time to explore the area and do some geocaching.  The main goal for the morning was to grab a number of caches (including "The Lookout") along the East Coast Trail.  It was a great hike in and out, resulting in him finding all 6 caches that he looked for.  Unfortunately, the fog was so heavy that you could hardly see ocean.  Not quite what he had hoped for, but oh well.  After signing the log and putting things back as he found them, J got back onto the trail to go find another one.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358433682"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-01T21:43:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22955729">theluckyfamily</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Love it. From West Coast to East Coast this was our target for this trip. Fav for sure. TFTC </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="62.568133333333336" lon="-110.33053333333334"><time>2001-07-13T00:00:00</time><name>GC1280</name><desc>Yankee/Doctor Bay Cache by The Grampian Armada</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1280</url><urlname>Yankee/Doctor Bay Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="4736" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Yankee/Doctor Bay Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>The Grampian Armada</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="15370">jeremycx</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Northwest Territories</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>An easy-to-find cache in the East Arm of Great Slave Lake.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The cache contains various donated items from each of four sailboats that made the journey to the cache location in the summer of 2001. Take and item/leave an item -- but make sure you record your presence in the logbook!</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Nestled in a crack between a large boulder and bedrock, this cache shouldn't be too hard to find.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1121998113"><groundspeak:date>2022-08-27T19:06:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42875274">flonkey</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">F</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="851339389"><groundspeak:date>2019-05-23T06:31:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26284854">Connecttcolcache</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Forgot to log but still really enjoyed it</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="30394017"><groundspeak:date>2007-07-30T00:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="398158">dadoo2</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I would love to visit Great Slave Lake some day and if I do I will find this cache.

Until then, I will dream about northern Canada.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="18749964"><groundspeak:date>2006-08-25T00:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="164938">Eclectic</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A victory, of sorts. I wanted to be the first to get to this cache, since it had been out there for 5 years and no visitors yet. No wonder, though; it took me a float plane ride to Lutselk'e and day and a half of paddling my kayak in order to get to it. Alas, someone by the call sign "Geo and Jan D." had beat me to it by a month. They signed the log book 23 Jul 2006, but have yet to register their visit on this site. I hope they made it back to civilization safe and sound. It took me another 11 days of paddling to do that!

Anyway, the cache is in pretty rough shape. Water has leaked in and everything was wet. It was near sunset when I found it, so I did not have time to properly dry everything out, nor did I have a better container. I did put the cache into a spare zip lock bag for added protection. Next person to go (in 5 more years?) had better bring a new container, plus a new log book. Coordinates were bang on, though. Took the Great Slave Lake banner, left a gold Buddha.   Eclectic</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="19847138"><groundspeak:date>2006-07-23T00:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="373633">Yola</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yola, our Ericson 35 sailboat, brought us into Yankee Bay (called Doctor Bay by the Yankee sawbones who summer here) and we ambled up to the cache, noted our visit with Sandy's Pen, left a key floater, took nothing and later regretted not clearing out the moist-to-soggy paper treasures.  Next one to visit it, please air it out and let it dry... and wonder just what the Grampian Fleet was up to that day back in '01.

George &amp; Janet D.
Christie Bay Rock Crunchers

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="44.588833" lon="-64.1725"><time>2000-06-28T00:00:00</time><name>GCBBA</name><desc>Geocache--Canada's 1st geocache by ken kane</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCBBA</url><urlname>Geocache--Canada's 1st geocache</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3002" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Geocache--Canada's 1st geocache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>ken kane</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="10664">eastriver</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="64" inc="0">Tree climbing required</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Nova Scotia</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Due to highway twining construction this cache has been moved temporarily to near East River Provincial (picnic) Park (across the road from the Park).The new co-ordinates are as indicated above.                                                             
This Canada's first Geocache and is located about 30 minutes from Halifax on a major highway. It is not difficult, but is meant to attract people using one of our main routes in NS( Hwy # 103). It is only a few minutes walk from the highway and is in a LARGE ammo can. Take some fly dope !!! This cache was originaly named GC41 but was relisted as GCBBA when caches were taken out of the (GC.com) site admin account and given to individuals. On 24th June/06 a geostone giving the details and co-ordinates of GCBBA was unveiled at an Event at Graves Island Provincial Park. The geostone is near the Administration Building in Graves Island Park, which is about 7 Km west of GCBBA on Highway #3. A short drive, with easy access to the Park. Access to the Park is available year round. When the gate is closed just walk up the paved road. This geostone was built and designed by Wallace_River. The sale of "Canada's First Geocache" geocoin paid for the Event. If you come from outside Nova Scotia I would love to know where you come from. Many thanks to those who take the time to post their pics. Keep them coming. It was confirmed by Geocaching HQ that GCBBA was Canada's first Traditional Cache to reach 500 Favorite Points. Thank you to all those who helped reach that goal, and many thanks to those who continue to add their Favorite Points.


</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Big rock.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363473801"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="526318">ZSteve</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found this one with HonuHideout today.  We're in the area for a very brief visit and spent the day exploring geocaching style.  It was a beautiful day to be out and I really enjoyed walking around the area and seeing the sights while finding caches.  We didn't have time to find all of the caches that we wanted to during our time here, but maybe we'll get a chance to come back again some time to find some more.  This one has been on my list for a long time, so it was great to finally be able to find it today.  Favorite Point from me.  Thanks for the fun!





</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363338750"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51000223">HonuHideout</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">So excited to have traveled from the cruise ship to get this highly sought after cache!  Took three TB’s, left three. Found it with ZSteve &amp; put green ink on the log! We’ve made our way to Canada via the cruise ship that left from Florida, USA for a fantastic 2026 geocaching trip. Any day is a great day when it includes Geocaching, right! Trying to keep up with my 100-day streak to meet a challenge.  TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364747077"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6174962">iicydiamonds</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you for maintaining this cache for so long! Although my travel companion is not a cacher, she thought that getting Canada's oldest sounded "really special", and agreed to a bit of a detour! And she was right, it was really special, even if I couldn't share the find with another actual cacher. My mom was still excited for me!

Left 3 TBs to continue their journeys!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362421139"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T07:02:57</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="335242">ScouterHerb &amp; MrsB</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">My caching name is ScouterHerb &amp; MrsB, although MrsB died in 2024. My daughter's were going to fly with  me to Nova Scotia to enable me to find GCBBA. However my arthritic legs are making it hard for me to find any cache let alone fly across the country for one. I will be 88 this summer. 

I did want to share the information I would have posted had I found it. 

I am from Sechelt, BC which is 4428 km West of GCBBA. A number of years ago I wondered how many Caches had been placed in the world in the first year of caching, May 3rd, 2000 to May 2nd, 2001. So, as a 10th Anniversary of Geocahing project, I decided to compile my own list, with a Canadian perspective. It turns out there were 2032 Caches placed in that period. Of those to date 1333 have been archived leaving 699 still available. You may view them on my web site at:   https://www.barge.ca/oldcachestotal.htm 60 of them were Canadian, of which 32 have been archived. 
GCBBA was of course the 1st placed in Nova Scotia,  the 1st placed in Canada and the 49th placed in the World. I have a list of all 699 still available at https://www.geocaching.com/plan/lists/BM7NXPA there are currently 8 of these disabled.
I would like to thank Ken Kane for keeping this one active and available. - Herb Barge

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362425696"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2300643">BOD21</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Petite visite rapide à Halifax pour le travail alors j’en profite pour faire une petite visite ici…</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="799270987"><groundspeak:date>2018-08-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I travel a lot for work.  I always try to sneak in a geocache or two (or 10) after work or by taking a later flight.  I haven’t been to Nova Scotia, so when the project came up in Halifax, I made some plans!  I was going to have TW (the wife) join me for a long weekend, but that didn’t work out, so I quickly switched to plan B.  I used Monday and Sunday as travel days and took a vacation day on Tuesday to explore Nova Scotia before my work and then on Friday evening high tailed it to New Brunswick followed by exploring Prince Edward Island on Saturday.  What a great trip it was!

My first stop of course was to get the oldest cache in Canada!  What a great spot.  I had never thought to use the middle of the exit ramp!  Brilliant!

Unfortunately, I should have done a bit more recon on the best path in, but I saw another car on the side of the ramp so I assumed they new more than I did and parked near by and went in from there.  We both took the hard way in and the easy way out.  He also scared the beans out of me as I was making my way to GZ.

Loved the giant container and the fun selfy sign.

Thanks for keeping this one going!

How could I not give it a favorite point?  Of course I did.

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="82.512" lon="-62.730333333333334"><time>2002-05-05T00:00:00</time><name>GC5803</name><desc>As North As It Gets! by Iceshelf 2002 Research Team</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC5803</url><urlname>As North As It Gets!</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="22531" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>As North As It Gets!</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Iceshelf 2002 Research Team</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="54417">franki</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Nunavut</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>A long hike and a rocky climb in the summer, a snowmobile is a better choice in the winter!</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This is the most Northern geocache placed to date.
&lt;p&gt;
This geocache was created by the crew of Iceshelf 2002. Iceshelf 2002 was a field trial carried out by Defence Research and Development Canada (Atlantic and Ottawa). Participants in the field trial included personnel from SPAWAR San Diego, Benthos Inc., University of Victoria, and Atmospheric and Environment Services. 
&lt;p&gt;
We have endured a month of camping on the ice of Jolliffe Bay, many visits by local polar bears, foxes, wolves and lemmings.  19 March - 16 May 2002.  Enjoy our cache! 
&lt;p&gt;
Container: white cubic plastic container with handle inside a green Reid's dairy milk crate. Container is within a cairn built from local rocks.  It is located in the lee of a large rock, see the photos.
&lt;p&gt;
WARNING there is a cairn nearby with a plaque on it built as a memorial to David Baade, do not mistake this for the cache!&lt;p&gt;

Content:&lt;UL&gt;
Iceshelf 2002 badges (2);&lt;br&gt;
Map;&lt;br&gt;
Navitrak WhereEver mapmaker CDs covering several national parks;&lt;br&gt;
Vise grips;&lt;br&gt;
Knife;&lt;br&gt;
KFP (knife, fork, spoon kit);&lt;br&gt;
rubber gloves;&lt;br&gt;
work gloves + liners;&lt;br&gt;
snow bucket and shovel (kid size);&lt;br&gt;
hand and foot warmers;&lt;br&gt;
toilet paper;&lt;br&gt;
3 sml floats;&lt;br&gt;
1 black golf ball;&lt;br&gt;
magic marker;&lt;br&gt;
pencils;&lt;br&gt;
staple remover;&lt;br&gt;
Post-it notes;&lt;br&gt;
a blank CD-RW.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The cache is on a promintory overlooking Jolliffe Bay near Canadian Forces Station Alert.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1132578059"><groundspeak:date>2022-10-18T16:38:32</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="40205041">Felixfelix10c</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Gg</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1121994387"><groundspeak:date>2022-08-27T20:19:17</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42941329">camuy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">J</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1013372623"><groundspeak:date>2021-04-27T17:28:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="27628907">RckyMtnFam</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">RckyMtnFam TFTC 👍🧨🤗</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1013386924"><groundspeak:date>2021-04-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="210210">TreePlanter</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Pretty snowy up there this time of year,  eh,  Rcky Mtn Fm  ??   LOL!!!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="982155001"><groundspeak:date>2020-12-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="210210">TreePlanter</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yes, I saw JvonN's bogus logs also.  I am happy they have been deleted on my caches.  I am sending a Travel Bug out here to post a photo of this fine caches log book.  Let's see the signatures here.  
We will see if it makes it.  LOL!    TBV33W</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.095767" lon="-79.282433"><time>2001-02-17T00:00:00</time><name>GC2B4</name><desc>Deer Bait by Peter Ferguson and kdkk17</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC2B4</url><urlname>Deer Bait</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="692" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Deer Bait</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Peter Ferguson and kdkk17</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="60881">kdkk17</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="9" inc="1">Significant hike</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="37" inc="1">Horses</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Ontario</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>"You won't come up "Short" if you head for the "Hills". Welcome to the "Oldest Cache in Ontario"! I would advise to stick to the trail, but then the logs are not nearly as fun to read.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Enjoy a pleasant walk, try No.2.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Rock.
Hint for Bonus -  Hip High Moss</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363810545"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T22:37:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1559511">cheifscout</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It was a great morning to walk the trails for this unique cache.
It was placed about 7 years before I started but I was so happy to have the chance to make this find on such a sunny day.
I met a fellow cacher from New Zealand at ground zero.
Log was wet but we managed to sign the cover.
Thanks for the cache- signed log
Cheifscout 
Took a travel bug and coin to move on.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359602842"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-07T10:14:24</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26561307">Mdk07</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is incredible! I am visiting Southern Ontario to see relatives and do some geocaching in another country for the week coming from Aurora, Colorado, USA. I just had to come out here for this one while I was in the area. It was so worth it! The park is beautiful and the cache is a nice classic hide in the woods. It is my first oldest cache in a Canadian Province and my first find in the Niagara Region. I left some swag and TBs. Thanks for keeping this one going for so long!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1356054465"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-19T10:17:25</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2178547">geolbite</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Another milestone for the books, but this time, for my 50th Birthday Celebration Find!! Working in eastern PA for a few weeks and visited my son's High School performance yesterday in Dayton, OH, for the WGI Indoor Percussion World Championship where their group came in 4th out of 53 scholastic competitors!! Decided to trip it back to PA by grabbing Ancient Lake, the oldest, or so I thought until this morning 🤔,  geocache in the state of OH (look up the "NovaNikki" cache page and the "Shawnee Lookout Cache" page for more details), then traverse Ontario from Detroit to Niagara Falls, and pick up 5his cache on my birthday!! 🎂🍰🧁

Beware these trails are slicker-n'-snot after a decent rain, so bring a good pair of boots unlike me in my daily hiker slick soles!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352917780"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-04T11:37:29</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3109903">Albertgirl</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hanging out in Niagara area with friends.

We aimed to get this cache to celebrate a couple milestones.  A nice hike, got back to the cars right before the rain started.

Thanks. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353017660"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-04T10:39:40</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13467866">Kdude146</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Cache Find #5000: After really pushing myself in March to get my find count up it was all worth it because today I had plans to do a day of Geocaching in Niagara Region and I really wanted to celebrate my milestone at the geocache that is considered the “Crown Jewel” of the caches in Ontario! I was joined today by Albertgirl, GeoBrosOXPC and OllyandPiper123. The hike was very pleasant from the parking lot to GZ. I actually found a really good quality hiking stick that I use for the hike and I decided to keep it. This geocache has been on my to-do list for years, but every time I’ve tried something has happened for it not to work out so I’m glad the stars finally aligned today so I could get it! This was a double milestone celebration because OllyandPiper123 got to celebrate find #1500 at the same time as me doing my 5000th. We got ourselves, logged into this and we did a bunch of photos to celebrate the occasion! Thank you so much for keeping this geocache active all these years! 


Favourite point added!

TFTC!




</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="46.255933" lon="-63.172067"><time>2001-08-28T00:00:00</time><name>GC1A17</name><desc>Charlottetown Memories by islanddunes/adopted from maryu in 2020</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1A17</url><urlname>Charlottetown Memories</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="6679" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Charlottetown Memories</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>islanddunes/adopted from maryu in 2020</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="11408384">islanddunes</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Large</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="53" inc="0">Park and grab</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Prince Edward Island</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>2023 Note- This cache is more difficult to get to after Hurricane Fiona. A lot of beautiful trees came down around it. I would suggest you access it from the back through open space/ field behind the park.

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This is PEI's first cache. It is located in a small memorial park about a 10 minute drive from downtown Charlottetown. It is much harder to get to than it use to.                        

Please leave a travel bug if you take a travel bug so that the cache always has a good inventory.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Follow the trail markers from the back.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364911650"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T17:36:46</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6004072">excited2explore</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We were in NS for a work/play vacation. We have 2 full days left before heading back to Edmonton. I got the green light from my mister to go for the oldest cache in PEI! MISSION ACCOMPLISHED at 1732 hrs! 

After some ‘important’ icon stops along the way we made our way here. Thanks to some excellent intel from a fellow cacher in NS during our event, we knew what to expect. We did take the path initially but realized our mistake and turned around. As we followed a marked path in, we marveled at the larger uprooted trees. WOW! Anyway, we’re so very grateful that this cache has been maintained despite the destruction around it. TFTH islanddunes and to maryu for maintaining this rare and special cache! Fave point added.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364453666"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8578903">Dr.Wave</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This was one of my target caches while travelling up the eastern seaboard. It earns a favourite point for being the first in PEI, for being the most neatly organised cache I've seen and for the very helpful marking tape guiding us in. Took one TB; left another. Thanks for keeping the oldie going. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361003051"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-14T18:34:10</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3354592">bikercamper</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I feel privileged to have been able to log the oldest cache in PEI. I hope it will be here for a ling time! Took nothing, left nothing but my stamp in Log book from NB TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358111699"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-30T16:25:44</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="691070">UBC Geograd</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tagging along while my wife is in Halifax for a conference. This means lots of free time and geocaches. In addition to NS caches, today involves a slight detour to visit NB and PEI, finding caches in both, including some specific types in order to meet some challenge caches back home. 

This was not to be missed and I set it up to be cache number 13000 for me. Incredible to see all the downed trees here, but glad the cache is safe and sound! Many thanks.

Proud to be a founding member of GEAA, the Geocaching Edmonton Area Association: www.geaa.ca</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1356199687"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21596724">Jems101</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Had to struggle through a lot of brambles but happy to log PEI's oldest cache while over here for an event. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="52.1972833333333" lon="-107.003666666667"><time>2001-01-07T00:00:00</time><name>GC14F</name><desc>Sask-cache-one by Donovan Onishenko</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC14F</url><urlname>Sask-cache-one</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="335" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Sask-cache-one</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Donovan Onishenko</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1514">donovano</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Saskatchewan</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>I believe this is the first cache in Saskatchewan, so I made it a fairly easy one.
&lt;p&gt;
A nice trail goes by it and it is a few metres off the trail.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>It is located about 20 Km (13 miles) from Saskatoon, along a gravel road.
&lt;p&gt;
I suggest parking at N52 12.122 W107 00.199 (though there is a road in).
&lt;p&gt;
Follow the trail south about half a kilometre and it will take you right past the cache.
It is a small green ammo can, fairly hidden from the path but can be seen when you are close.
&lt;p&gt;
It contains:&lt;br&gt;
-Log book and letter on Geocaching&lt;br&gt;
-Deck of cards, a dog chew, mini headphones, phone cord splitter, eyeglass screwdriver, 6 foot tape measure, 2 flashlights with batteries, 2 key chains, 4AA batteries, a brass compas, a blank cd-r, a 100Mb ZIP disk, a pair of gloves, 2 golf balls, 2 rubber balls, a mini slinky, a chemical light stick, waterproof matches, a mosquito net for your hat, a sweater defuzzing comb, a water pistol, some chemical hand warmers.
&lt;p&gt;
A lot of stuff, so the can is farily full, but I got it all in there. This is along a public road allowance, and the cache is just on my girlfriends property so you won't be tresspassing.
&lt;p&gt;
I do ask that if you open a gate though (you should not have to) please close it (and if it already open, leav it open).
&lt;p&gt;
This area has a lot of deer and birds if you walk quietly and lots of berry bushes can be found along the way. When I placed the cache, I used skiies but there are enough snowmobile trails that walking should not be a problem.
&lt;p&gt;
The cache itself is below the snow line, so you may want to take a copy of the hints below.
&lt;p&gt;
Happy hunting!</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>As you reach the top of the first hill, there will be a bent tree to the west, forming an upside down U. A few metres west of that tree is a tree that has fallen over and near the top it hits several smaller bushes and dead trees. I have placed the cache in this cluster of brush.
</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364834244"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T09:17:30</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5479012">BackRoadTravelers12</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I'm going to add this to my favorite file. TFTC </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362969972"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T13:55:10</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="20743821">snow_canada</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC! And the short adventure :)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362698850"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T13:06:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="833553">tatie</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Together with Geochum, we continue our journey westward. We take the opportunity to find a few caches here and there along the way.

Happy to find this first cache!

Thanks for the cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363457948"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4067764">Géochum</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I found it with Tatie.
Thank you for the nice cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362471835"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3316995">fylion</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">With SCAR2026 starting tomorrow (my first caching event!), I figured it was a good opportunity to check out the oldest cache in the province, and so made the trek out of the city in the morning. After a lovely drive up to the area and an interesting gate to open and close, it was a nice calm walk down the path through the quiet field. Once I got into the woods it only took me a couple of minutes of wandering to see something slightly conspicuous and VERY suspicious - Sask Cache One!

Took a few photos for my own memories and signed the log. If an out-of-province cacher ever visits me, I'll be sure to take them to this spot - both for the history and for the beautiful setting. Thanks for keeping this maintained, even 25 years after its first creation!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="60.712066666666665" lon="-135.46391666666668"><time>2001-05-20T00:00:00</time><name>GCA13</name><desc>Scout Lake Road cache by maphew</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCA13</url><urlname>Scout Lake Road cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="2579" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Scout Lake Road cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>maphew</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="8983">maphew</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Yukon Territory</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>At the end of the Scout Lake road. A little climbing involved but it's easy (we had a crew of children with us).</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>GPS coords were captured with an older (5 yrs) Trimble Scout and have been converted (via eTrex Vista) from NAD27 to WGS84. 
&lt;p&gt;
The cache is probably locatable without a GPS by a person willing to do some legwork. It is planted near a distinctive local landmark.
&lt;p&gt;
The container is a 500ml clear plastic peanut butter jar with a green lid. Hopefully it can survive being opened in subzero temperatures. Anybody who sets out to find this cache in the winter should bring a pencil - the little girl who's contribution to the cache was to be a pencil decided at the last minute that she really didn't want to part with it. :)
&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;
Update:&lt;/i&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
I've been told the road was washed about 5km before the cache site at the beginning of June and is impassable to vehicles. Mountain bikes, 4 wheelers, etc. should be still be okay with a little work.


</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1314733206"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3377807">Arkanada110</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This one was the target for the day. The road, while very bumpy, didn't stand up to my Ford Explorer. 4x4 took me to within ~500 m of the cache. After that, I had to hike in. After a hot climb and a short hunt, I found the first cache in the Yukon. Definitely proud to have found it! Left two of my Pathtags for future finders. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1300739084"><groundspeak:date>2025-05-25T14:24:43</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2662789">doolins</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Entogeek found the cache. Three words - it was epic. Very little was as expected, except that the journey was the story of legends, the view from GZ could inspire a new John Denver song, don't bring your own vehicle, and make sure you wear denim.  Thank you for a great challenge and a better reward.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1300766276"><groundspeak:date>2025-05-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="788388">entogeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Much thought was given in planning access to this cache, the oldest one in the Yukon.  After reading previous logs, we decided the best course of action would be to rent a 4x4 pickup truck here in Whitehorse and its a good thing we did as we surely would have ripped out the bottom of the Honda CRV we had traversed the country in (which by the way was stolen while I was at work a couple of months ago; thank goodness for the GPS tracker I had installed so it could be found and eventually returned to me).  Back to the cache at hand.  The first washout is virtually impassable with a normal vehicle should you choose to drive up it as it consists of gravel and large, loose cobblestones, and after that there are numerous washouts you will have to contend with and without cell service you'll realize you made a bad decision when you bottom out and either get stuck, or worse, rip off your oil pan.  When we came to a fork in the road, we made the wrong decision at first by going left, and backtracked a couple of minutes to take the right fork.  Eventually we made it to within about 550 m of the cache and rather than risk going downhill and driving back up on loose gravel, we decided to walk from there.  The forest was carpeted with thick moss and I felt kind of guilty for squishing it beneath my feet but it rebounded quickly.  The climb up the hill was arduous to say the least and I hung onto the occasional aspen to catch my breath.  But all of my huffing and puffing was rewarded with a breathtaking view from the top.  Not sure how the CO could describe it as an easy climb, maybe we came in from the wrong direction?  Anyway, the cache was easily located and we're happy to report it's in good shape and awaits discovery.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1258150361"><groundspeak:date>2024-09-04T17:01:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1185612">MI3sprouts</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">An epic day of making a drive and then taking the long hike from the washout out to ground zero.  At the washout it said 3.7 miles as the crow flies to ground zero when we started walking.  Saw a couple of bikers and two hunter gals along the way but other than that it was relatively quiet.  When we got about .3 miles from Ground Zero we ran into major water on the road so took a diversion to the left and were able to find a way around before we started hiking up the big hill and then the smaller secondary hill. A light rain was with us towards the end but had a great level of satisfaction in finding the container and taking in the view from the top.  Definitely worth the trip and the hike. Thanks.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1256248877"><groundspeak:date>2024-08-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1185612">MI3sprouts</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Curious as to whether another option to access the cache is from the east coming out of Whitehorse.  My daughter and I will be driving through the area in very early October and are considering the option of renting an ATV in Whitehorse and taking that out to the cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.720633" lon="-85.985967"><time>2000-10-23T00:00:00</time><name>GC93</name><desc>Indiana's First by Wandrer Maintained by IN_Darel</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC93</url><urlname>Indiana's First</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="147" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Indiana's First</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Wandrer Maintained by IN_Darel</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1406142">IN_Darel</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="17" inc="1">Poisonous plants</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Indiana</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;b&gt;Indiana Information&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Indiana's name comes from the Indiana Territory created in 1800 when the U.S. Congress separated all or part of five states from the Northwest Territory. The territorial name was retained when Indiana became a state in 1816. The name of the capital city, Indianapolis, was derived from the state name plus "polis," a Greek word meaning "city." The origin of the nickname "Hoosier" is still being debated. One explanation is that it comes from the common Indiana settler's shouted response of "Who's yere?" to a knock on the door. One story is that a settler's ear was cut off somehow and from the question, "Whose ear?," a phonetic contraction developed into "Hoos-ear." Another more likely version is that a contractor named Sam Hoosier, who built a canal along the Ohio River preferred to hire men living north of the river, believing them to be better workers than those living south of the river. Most of those coming from north of the river were from Indiana, and were called "Hoosier's men." Eventually all people from Indiana came to be known as Hoosiers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Population:&lt;/b&gt; Although Indiana ranks only 38th in geographical area among the 50 states, it is 14th in population. The U.S. Census Bureau in 2000 counted over 6 million residents.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Area:&lt;/b&gt; 36,291 square miles or 93,993 square kilometers. Extreme length, 275 miles; average breadth, 144 miles. Highest altitude, 1,257 feet or 383 meters in Wayne County; lowest altitude, 320 feet or 97 meters in Posey County.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Capital:&lt;/b&gt; Indianapolis&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Motto:&lt;/b&gt; The Crossroads of America (Adopted in 1937).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Flower:&lt;/b&gt; Peony. (Adopted 1957)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Tree:&lt;/b&gt; Tulip tree (yellow poplar) (Adopted in 1931).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Bird:&lt;/b&gt; Cardinal (Adopted in 1933).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Song:&lt;/b&gt; "On the Banks of the Wabash," by Paul Dresser (Adopted in 1913).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Poem:&lt;/b&gt; "Indiana," by Arthur Franklin Mapes, Kendallville (Adopted in 1963).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Seal:&lt;/b&gt; The seal depicts a pioneer scene; a woodsman felling a tree while a buffalo flees from the forest across the plains. Adopted officially in 1963.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Flag:&lt;/b&gt; The Indiana flag displays 19 gold stars and a gold torch on a field of blue. The torch is said to stand for liberty and enlightenment; the rays represent far-reaching influence. The stars in the outer circle represent the 13 original states; those in the inner arc represent the five states next admitted to the Union. The star above the torch stands for Indiana, the 19th state. Adopted 1917.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;State Name:&lt;/b&gt; Congress coined the name Indiana, which means "Land of the Indians," when in 1800 it separated an area containing all or part of five present states from the Northwest Territory and named the separated areas the "Indiana Territory." The territorial name was retained when Indiana became a state&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hint #1: I can neither confirm nor deny that the best place to park a vehicle is at: N41°43.253 W085°59.170 .&lt;br /&gt;
Hint #2: I can neither confirm nor deny that a boat would be helpful in finding this cache.&lt;br /&gt;
Hint #3: I can neither confirm nor deny that night caching is not recommended.&lt;br /&gt;
[Edit Nov-5-2001]&lt;br /&gt;
=====&lt;br /&gt;
Modified cache to increase rating/difficulty based on the Geocache Rating System. Also added hints.&lt;br /&gt;
=====&lt;br /&gt;
[Edit July-03-2006]&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Updated cache type and page.&lt;br /&gt;
=====&lt;br /&gt;
[Edit July-04-2006]&lt;br /&gt;
Barnaby Jones was FTF on the new hide! Thanks for adding the 50 Cal Ammo can!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="blue"&gt;Cache container is a 50 Cal Ammo Can.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
~~ 3-16-09: Cache was placed using a Yellow Garmin which could result in a slight difference if you are using a better GPS.
&lt;hr /&gt;
=====&lt;br /&gt;
~~ 3-31-22: Container was moved from private property to public access area and coordinates were updated.
&lt;hr /&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Hints arent going to help you on this one. You are on your own. Have fun and post your comments when you find the cache.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364875296"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T14:55:37</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4239635">Jeph_Gileadite</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It's great to scratch off Indiana's oldest cache off my list. Surprise, this cache hasn't gotten muggled since it is so close to a trail.  But all is well with this cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364023875"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="16271950">grandmabonnie44</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for keeping this oldie alive.  Slowly finding them all in each state. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364023952"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T09:58:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="468159">cjhanson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Stopping for the oldest cache in Indiana on our road trip east. I found this one several years ago, but my friend grandmaBonnie44 hadn’t found it yet.
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363966396"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="382938">incepit</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A quick find here while working on a road trip getting notable caches, mostly the oldest in each state.  Thanks for the fun.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363730177"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T11:38:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5548736">triforce66</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Had to get on our way to the Ohio Pizza Geotrail. Tftc </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="32.8782" lon="-116.4641"><time>2000-09-10T00:00:00</time><name>GC5B</name><desc>Phil's Memorial Cache (Oldest CA. Cache) by GoodDogSD </desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC5B</url><urlname>Phil's Memorial Cache (Oldest CA. Cache)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="91" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Phil's Memorial Cache (Oldest CA. Cache)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>GoodDogSD </groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="128956">Duncan!</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="0">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="0">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="0">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="0">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="0">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>California</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;California’s oldest geocache and first in San Diego County!&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Elevation: 5,483 ft.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;After visiting California's very first Geocache, the dearly departed LAX cache, I left this one, the state's second, on 09-10-00 as a kind of memorial to my dog, Phil, who loved to hike with me to explore the mountains of San Diego's east county. Subsequently, this stash is set along one of his most favorite hikes, and contains treasures for both Geocachers and Geocanines!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cache may be frozen or buried under snow in winter. Also be sure to watch out for rattlesnakes!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After finding the cache, continue to the big lake for a truly spectacular view of the valley (looks like the "Ponderosa"). Also, very cool ancient Native American stone grinding holes can be found on a big flat rock at &lt;a href="https://goo.gl/maps/7rVjgUUcCkYKpfRu7"&gt;N32'52.512 W116'27.854&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You probably should purchase a National Forest Service Adventure Pass in order to park legally in the Cleveland National Forest Recreation Area ($5.00 for the single day pass). I have seen lots of people park there without a pass and seldom get cited, so it's up to you whether you want to spend the time and money to get the pass or take the risk of a ticket and fine. If you want to purchase an Adventure Pass, you can buy one at any Big 5 Sporting Goods store, the Mount Laguna Visitor's Center (&lt;a href="https://goo.gl/maps/EQT3gmVzDTkrjLNPA"&gt;N32'52.015 W116'25.111&lt;/a&gt;), or next door at the Mount Laguna Lodge and Trading Post.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Happy hunting!&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Your best option for parking is at the map area near the 19 mile marker on Sunrise Highway.  Then, you can either hike around the hill to the south (much prettier with cool shade, but more climbing), or the less scenic flat open meadow hike heading N/W from the parking area.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363371072"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13302210">theTwonky</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Well here it is - the one we came for. Searched for a bit then consulted the pics in prior logs. One pic helped narrow it down and we made the find!

Dropped a pathtag.
TFTC!

___
GasStationTuna and I drove down from Los Angeles to finally find California's oldest cache. We had a blast -as usual- hiking through the woods and fields along the way. We made 13 total finds on the day. Thanks to all the COs that added to our fun!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363224567"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T11:30:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="16067991">GasStationTuna</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">theTwonky and I headed to the area to go after California’s oldest! And we grabbed several other caches along the trail! This was not just one of them. It was the entire reason we drove three hours together. 

We zeroed in on the cache area, but ground zero was absolutely full of hidey holes and hosts. The photo gallery was invaluable for us. And after some detective work, we were able to triangulate the relative location among all the stuff at GZ. And a more thorough search brought us right to the container!

This one was definitely worth the trip to the area and the hike in. I grabbed a few trackables that I’ll move along. 

There were no problems with this hide today. It was a somewhat kinda quick find, sign, and replace! 

Thank you, Duncan! for the Traditional! Thank you for the new smiley on my map! And thank you for adding another month to my Jasmer grid!

This is Find #5732 for me!


• - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - • 


Unless otherwise noted here, the cache was in good condition at the time it was found by me today.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361545043"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-16T10:13:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="40921869">HippieTwo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Today we left the Legends Party Nick's work was hosting for him and went on a caching run to get the oldest in CA and the webcam just north of us.  We added in whatever we could in the time we had. The National Forest was so pretty. We took tons of pictures but we know it won't do the area justice. The day started out a little chill but warmed up to perfection. There were a lot of people out enjoying biking and hiking the trails! We both got a little red from the sun but it wasn't too bad. We both got a little scratched up from some of the bushwhacking, but that's the geocaching life. 

We finished the night with a formal "gala" back with his work functions so we had to rinse the forest off and look presentable! 

The coveted oldie!!  It actually took way longer to find this once we got to gz than it really should've been.  It was very nicely tucked away!  We dropped off some more trackables.

Thank you for the cache </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361018488"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-14T18:10:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="609455">Data Wrangler</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Took me a while to find the right trailhead, then I read the cache page and knew what I needed to do. Favorite. SL, TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360933196"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-14T08:35:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="55383826">sillysquirrel26</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">05/14/2026*none*
Transferring my find history to a new account. Found on the original date noted. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="47.374033" lon="-121.337983"><time>2000-06-21T00:00:00</time><name>GCD</name><desc>Geocache (GCD) by hydnsek (originally A.J. &amp; Karen)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCD</url><urlname>Geocache (GCD)</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="13" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Geocache (GCD)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>hydnsek (originally A.J. &amp; Karen)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="94792">hydnsek</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="9" inc="1">Significant hike</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="62" inc="1">Seasonal access</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="0">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Washington</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Take a hike up the flanks of Mount Margaret - in the Cascade Mountains near Snoqualmie Pass - to the oldest active cache in Washington State and 15th-oldest in the world, with the only remaining three-digit GC code. It's a Great Caching Day!
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/gs-geo-images/02ff2580-1959-401a-b2f8-d441f86d82ed.jpg" align="right" hspace="7" /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Getting there:&lt;/b&gt; The optimal route to this cache starts at the Mount Margaret trailhead (see waypoint). Take exit 54 from I-90, then unpaved forest roads 4832 and 4934 to trailhead parking (GPS routing is usually accurate). The roads are generally in good shape; sometimes, however, the final stretch to parking has big potholes and dips that might defeat a low-slung sedan or fifth-wheel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You don't need a pass to park at the trailhead; it's free.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The hike:&lt;/b&gt; From there, the hike is 2 miles one way with 1,600 feet of elevation gain. Follow the Mount Margaret Trail until you are about 300 feet from the cache. The cache isn't on the trail, so you have two options: Bushwhack directly to the cache location through the brush, or follow the trail past the cache location to the ridge, take in the views, then follow the sketchy ridgeline track until you see the waytrail down to the cache, which is just below the ridge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a moderate mountain hike, so bring hiking shoes, water, and other backcountry essentials. Don't forget your camera! Weather permitting, you'll have nice views of Mount Rainier and the Snoqualmie Pass area, as well as great views east from the ridge top into the Alpine Lakes Wilderness.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/gs-geo-images/6f5e0f98-b686-4da3-ac81-fb154f33826b.jpg" align="left" hspace="7" /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;When to go:&lt;/b&gt; This area of the Cascades can have snow well into the summer (often into July), so plan your trip accordingly. Your chances of reaching and finding the cache in deep snow are almost nil, and simply visiting the location does not qualify as a find. Optimal months are July through October. You may want to check &lt;a href="http://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?lat=47.427739&amp;amp;lon=-121.417465#.VnY0Unt57xI"&gt;Snoqualmie Pass weather&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/traffic/passes/snoqualmie/default.aspx?imgparam=4"&gt;I-90 road conditions&lt;/a&gt; to prepare for your trip.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The cache:&lt;/b&gt; The container is a 30cal ammo can.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Pro tip:&lt;/b&gt; Go in August or early September if you want to snack on ripe huckleberries en route to the cache. Yum!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Cell reception:&lt;/b&gt; A few folks have asked.... Verizon has great coverage; AT&amp;amp;T has a few spotty areas. T-Mobile, not so much. However, if you save the cache(s) offline in your geo-app of choice, cell reception won't be an issue.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Origins:&lt;/b&gt; The original cache, placed in June 2000 by ajroman and his girlfriend Karen, was famously a recipe box found at a yard sale for 10 cents. I found this cache on June 27, 2004, back when it was just an ordinary cache in a young game. Years later (2011), AJ asked me to adopt it as they didn't geocache anymore and it had become a celebrity cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While you're here, you really should get &lt;a href="http://coord.info/GC1GF1N"&gt;Mount Margaret&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://coord.info/GC31H5Q"&gt;Livin' on the Edge&lt;/a&gt;. Both offer breath-taking viewpoints over the area (but are not recommended for acrophobes).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you use a Garmin or DeLorme GPSr, &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.switchbacks.com/maps/NW_Trails.html"&gt;Northwest Trails&lt;/a&gt; could prove helpful.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;In Memorium: Eric McDonald (ECM41)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
On Aug. 17, 2014, geocacher Eric McDonald (ECM41) was hiking to this cache before the &lt;a href="http://coord.info/GC4MHAQ"&gt;Going APE mega-event&lt;/a&gt;, along with his 12yo daughter Kaylynn and best friend Hoovers69, when he had a heart attack. Despite more than an hour of CPR, Eric died on the trail before paramedics could reach him. A Puyallup resident, Eric was only 43 and in good shape, and was at the Groundspeak Block Party the day before, so this was a huge shock. He is greatly missed in the Puget Sound caching community.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Page views&lt;/b&gt; added Oct. 4, 2012. The cache was placed in June 2000, so this counter doesn't begin to capture all the visitors to this page, but it's still fun to see:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;b&gt;&lt;a href="http://info.flagcounter.com/13f"&gt;&lt;img src="http://s06.flagcounter.com/count/13f/bg_FFFFFF/txt_3E7540/border_CCCCCC/columns_8/maxflags_50/viewers_0/labels_1/pageviews_0/flags_1/" alt="free counters" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/b&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Ammo can behind end stump in row of stumps.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364498708"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T21:43:49</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3330050">Stephi_Dita</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wow, what a fantastic geocaching day this turned out to be!

Starting from Portland, I first visited the location where the very first geocache was placed. From there, I continued on to Oregon’s oldest active cache. Later, as I headed north into Washington, I had the opportunity to add yet another highlight to an already memorable day by visiting this cache.

An unforgettable experience and definitely one of the highlights of my geocaching adventures. Thanks for maintaining this legendary oldie!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364500776"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2492813">RockWrangler</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The Wranglers Sets Sail - Returning Home 

The Wranglers hit the lower 48 this morning (6AM) on our return from Alaska on the Norwegian Bliss. We all around had a fantastic time with great family and friends. But Rock said we had so mud time before boarding our red eye flight tonight. So caching we go. APE Cache and Iron Horse were up first - okay, not so bad at all. A warm up. Onto GCD…

WOW. That’s a hike. We felt a bit better about ourselves when we looked it up on AllTrails and saw that this is not just a moderate hike, but a “hard” one. PACE YOURSELVES. It all in all was 4.36mi roundtrip with about 1700ft elevation gain (did some bushwhacking at the end we probably didn’t need to do). We were probably going faster than we needed to but finished in 2 hours and 15 minutes. 

The view halfway up your ascent is so beautiful. However the cloud cover really started soaking us and the rain gear had to come out. We packed lots of water and snacks. Poles would’ve been handy but not 100% necessary. We consider ourselves in shape 20-somethings and it was still one of the hardest hikes we’ve personally done. The Mrs gave it a thumbs down while logging at the top but by the end thought it was worth it. 

Caches found on the trail along the way were in great condition - and the memorial was very kind and a good reminder. TFTC! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363978851"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2824625">garretslarrity</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#5 of 5 today on my drive from Portland to Bellevue, with GCD being the main target.

Speaking of which, I've done it. But boy I was scared I would fail.

For context, I first attempted GCD back in 2023. My company flew me out to Seattle for a conference. Problem is, that was in February. I drove to the area after successfully getting the APE cache, but it quickly became obvious that GCD was not going to happen. The road to the trailhead was snowed in, to say nothing of the mountain.

Fast forward to 2026. My company is again bringing me to the area for a conference, this time in Bellevue, and this time in May. Weather permitting, I can get it. And when I saw people find it earlier this month, I knew this was my chance.

But on the drive here, I start to worry that I will fail again. I worry about not having warm enough clothes, and then I worry about the weather. It started raining on the drive up, and I didn't even check the weather this morning. I'm from California and we don't really think about the possibility of this whole "rain" thing y'all have up here. But that was closer to the coast and then I check the weather for Snoqualmie Pass and it says it's not raining, but that it may later in the evening. And what if it is on the mountain? Will it be snowing there? I'm so scared. 

But worse, I'm not making good time. I should have left Portland earlier, I just had to stop in 4 different counties to get caches, which took me longer than I planned, and then between Memorial Day and some crashes the traffic was worse than I planned for. I don't arrive at the trailhead parking until 4:30.

I see that others had said you can make the round trip in less than 3 hours, but I can't be too confident since it may take longer to find the cache or I may take the wrong trail. Indeed I did take the wrong trail at first, but corrected that soon enough. But being so scared I ran up the mountain. I got pretty sweaty despite it being so cold. I chose to skip all other caches except this one.

Ultimately, I made it up to GZ pretty quickly. Little more than an hour once I was on the right trail. It did not rain, let alone snow, and there was just a few patches of snow until you got to the very top. After some wayfinding, I reach GZ and find something that matches the hint, and there's the cache, right where it said it would be. I have found GCD!!! The oldest cache in the State of Washington and the last living 1 character GC code!

Open up that beautiful ammo can, sign the log, and take a sigh of relief. I made it. I won. Now I just need to make it back down alive.

Having made such good time, I could have found some of the other caches, but after such a stressful day to get to this point, I decide to instead relax and enjoy the hike down. There, I reflect on how perfect this vacation was, and how wonderful my life is. Frankly, I needed that.

I make it down, and drive through the dirt roads, and then once I'm back on the asphalt is when it starts raining. Mother Nature knew I was coming, so she held it for me. We're pretty tight.

hydnsek, thank you so much for maintaining this cache after so many years. This was an amazing adventure. TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363355617"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4942266">geogooose</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This one was a major goal for the trip and I'm glad that we found it. The hike up was a bit challenging but manageable. We spotted a few little patches of snow but it looks like most of it is melted at this point. The view at the top was pretty incredible. Thanks for the cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363359349"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T10:05:01</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15626224">caseander</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We made it to the find! So cool to find the oldest cache in WA and wow, what a view from up there! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="438032970"><groundspeak:date>2014-08-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I first heard about this cache a few years ago when friends went the the block party and then more in 2013 when I did go to the Block Party and APE but didn't try GCD.  I'm very very glad we did it this year.

We took it easy with plenty of stops and leap-froged Pan and his group a few times both on the way up and down.  I the view on the trail and from the ridge line are simply breathtaking.  I was particularly happy to have my son Puzzle Painter on the trail with me.  He as well as Taz and MOS made for great company.

This is truly a special place.

This is my fist Oldest Active in a State and my earliest Jasmer find.  And will be one I remember for a long time.

I was heartbroken to hear of Eric's passing and my heart goes out to his daughter. What a tragedy.  I did see the small memorial that Brewman Pete &amp; Co left on the way down.  At the time I didn't know what it was for, but I recall it was striking.  A special thanks to Minna of vipema and Hoovers69... I know how long those many minutes must have been for the first responders who maintained CPR until EMS showed up.  Thank you.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="45.565483" lon="-75.774433"><time>2001-05-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC958</name><desc>Beware of the pit (v2) by 300mag</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC958</url><urlname>Beware of the pit (v2)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Multi-cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="2392" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Beware of the pit (v2)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>300mag</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="3375">300mag</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Multi-cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Québec</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is a multi waypoints cache.(The first one stashed in
Canada)</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>I have re-activated,refreshed and upgraded the difficulty level of
the cache.These are the coordinates to start from. They are the old
church coords.You can park behind the church(near the
cemetery).Once there you will see a field. At the end of it there
use to be a few old shacks.Now only a cement floor exist. Near it
the first waypoint coords are (POSTED)(post);). After getting this
waypoint coord and clue... just follow the trail on your right of
the field to the next waypoint. Most are near the trail. You will
walk through the pit. It is a nice trail mostly flat and clear sky
but with a few hills. You might want to bring water. There's lots
of atv's or mountain bikes also some nice views of camp fortune ski
hills and environment Canada sats dishes. You will also see a
fallen tree pointing in the caches direction. Historicaly this is
the first multi-cache ever created :) Have fun 300mag</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>There is five waypoints before arriving to the actuall cache. The cache is number six. Most of the waypoints have clues to the other.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="350452899"><groundspeak:date>2013-09-14T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3897955">Xira</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Lostinthegarden were interested in finding this cache. Knowing my 'penchant for multis', they thought it might interest me and invited me along. I had looked at it in the past but it didn't seem to be what it used to be so I hadn't ever made the trip before. However, I was happy to accept that invitation knowing that I'd enjoy caching with them and that finding Canada's first multi would be a awesome bonus.

After picking up a few other caches along the way, we got going on this one. Fee&amp;Me's notes were our guide. WP1 and WP2 were easily found. Then we took the easy way over to WP5 and then on to the final, where we came upon the unhappy truth that this cache is well and truly gone. [:(]

The trees on the site have been bulldozed and tons of fill loaded in on top of them. GZ is just about in the middle of a building pad. We all peered down the edges hoping that the container might have somehow escaped but there was nothing to see. Given how the leaves on the bulldozed tree have just barely started to shrivel, I think we missed finding this cache by just a matter of days. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="350119558"><groundspeak:date>2013-09-14T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2801553">lostinthegarden</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Quel dommage... it looks like this one is gone for good.

We had really looked forward to finding this historic cache, even in its altered state.  Alas, it was not to be.  We had no problems finding the info at WP1 and WP2 (what a great view from the latter!), and WP5 was also in good shape.  Our hopes faded when we got to the final location, however... the entire area around GZ has been bulldozed, filled, and leveled in preparation for building a house (roof trusses and other building materials were already on site).  It looks like this work took place just in the last few weeks. [:(]  We wandered around the periphery, hoping to spot some remnants of the cache container, but if it's still out there, it must now be entombed under many tons of rock and gravel.

It's a real bummer that we were a little too late to find it, but kudos to 300mag for putting out this groundbreaking cache, and to Fee&amp;me for her efforts to keep it going.

The good news is that Coco7 is putting out a new multi in the pit area that in some sense will carry on this legacy.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="337400292"><groundspeak:date>2013-07-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4188552">Les Smarties</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">bien contente d'accompagner moumoute dixquatre-2 et ouestcharly pour trouver cette belle cache que je ne connaissait même pas l'existance...wow la première multi, toujours bien en place et en bon état;c'est pas rien!!!MPLC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="335373472"><groundspeak:date>2013-07-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1366649">dixquatre2</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Les autres l'ont trouvé avant moi.  MPLC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="334650695"><groundspeak:date>2013-07-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2210809">moumoute</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Comme c'est malheureux que cette vieille cache ait été archivée. Elle est encore bien en place. Les vieilles  caches sont si rares ... et on parle ici de la première multi au Québec ...
Je passe la signer en compagnie de maman Smarties et Dixquatre2
merci 300mag pour la cache et aux geocacheurs du coin de l'avoir maintenue</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="33.6225" lon="-86.601667"><time>2019-02-12T11:32:57</time><name>P1126</name><cmt>Primary Parking near the obliesk at the Veteran's Memorial</cmt><desc>Primary Parking</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=52800690-70bf-43d0-a5c1-2f485b1c9be3</url><urlname>Primary Parking</urlname><sym>Parking Area</sym><type>Waypoint|Parking Area</type></wpt><wpt lat="33.626767" lon="-86.603067"><time>2013-11-27T18:23:07</time><name>PC126</name><cmt>Parking area nearby if all spots are taken at Veterans Memorial</cmt><desc>Masonic Park alternate parking area</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=4bdc2185-493e-4bdd-bcad-b38447023a3b</url><urlname>Masonic Park alternate parking area</urlname><sym>Parking Area</sym><type>Waypoint|Parking Area</type></wpt><wpt lat="39.091783" lon="-105.454433"><time>2012-01-05T10:39:13</time><name>OL18</name><cmt>This is a waypoint marking the original location of this cache before it was moved.</cmt><desc>Original Location</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=c25e0185-708a-4aa8-a20b-8edae8899193</url><urlname>Original Location</urlname><sym>Reference Point</sym><type>Waypoint|Reference Point</type></wpt><wpt lat="39.092583" lon="-105.451583"><time>2023-09-10T09:29:22</time><name>PK18</name><cmt>If you don't have high clearance, or the road is muddy, you will want to park here and walk to the cache. Otherwise, you can drive pretty close, and pull off to the side.</cmt><desc>Parking</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=dd89605a-4ed9-4e04-946d-1ab0f440b2f8</url><urlname>Parking</urlname><sym>Parking Area</sym><type>Waypoint|Parking Area</type></wpt><wpt lat="38.527283" lon="-75.483917"><time>2021-06-13T05:56:28</time><name>EN10A</name><cmt /><desc>Park Entrance</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=992ad9d1-e105-4d86-81b5-6dab10a473ca</url><urlname>Park Entrance</urlname><sym>Reference Point</sym><type>Waypoint|Reference Point</type></wpt><wpt lat="38.525133" lon="-75.479867"><time>2021-06-13T05:56:28</time><name>TH10A</name><cmt>Many trails can be found near the Bald Cypress Nature Center.</cmt><desc>Trails</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=386b73ca-5922-4672-acd6-b2fd4e052c92</url><urlname>Trails</urlname><sym>Trailhead</sym><type>Waypoint|Trailhead</type></wpt><wpt lat="48.5165" lon="-116.817733"><time>2019-07-08T13:12:39</time><name>0125</name><cmt>Depart the East Shore Rd onto gravel</cmt><desc>Leave pavement</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=ef1a4992-c27a-47ce-bb7f-70f5d71202ef</url><urlname>Leave pavement</urlname><sym>Reference Point</sym><type>Waypoint|Reference Point</type></wpt><wpt lat="48.5165" lon="-116.816033"><time>2019-07-08T13:12:39</time><name>0225</name><cmt>Go left at the fork onto Camels Prairie Rd</cmt><desc>Stay left</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=5d5d716d-18cb-4ba5-a1f2-ff06ed2e0871</url><urlname>Stay left</urlname><sym>Reference Point</sym><type>Waypoint|Reference Point</type></wpt><wpt lat="48.538267" lon="-116.798683"><time>2019-07-08T13:12:39</time><name>0325</name><cmt>Turn right (south)</cmt><desc>Turn right</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=df0cf310-81e3-4162-b5bf-87e352e1df3f</url><urlname>Turn right</urlname><sym>Reference Point</sym><type>Waypoint|Reference Point</type></wpt><wpt lat="48.526433" lon="-116.794433"><time>2019-07-08T13:12:39</time><name>0425</name><cmt>Stay left at the fork and climb</cmt><desc>Stay left</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=4632f5aa-d363-4d31-b089-77ca054ae5cf</url><urlname>Stay left</urlname><sym>Reference Point</sym><type>Waypoint|Reference Point</type></wpt><wpt lat="48.555367" lon="-116.783967"><time>2019-07-08T13:12:39</time><name>0525</name><cmt>Stay right at fork and climb</cmt><desc>Stay right</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=4a8c3848-4bcf-4598-b30f-2f0f44bfa5c7</url><urlname>Stay right</urlname><sym>Reference Point</sym><type>Waypoint|Reference Point</type></wpt><wpt lat="48.545667" lon="-116.77485"><time>2019-07-08T13:12:39</time><name>0625</name><cmt>This spot is a good place to park if you do not have a high-clearance vehicle. From here, it is about a 1.4 mile/2.3 km hike up to the cache. If your vehicle can make it, head uphill!</cmt><desc>Park or head uphill</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=2701d92d-ab2c-4484-905a-ec5801263f1b</url><urlname>Park or head uphill</urlname><sym>Parking Area</sym><type>Waypoint|Parking Area</type></wpt><wpt lat="48.5398" lon="-116.7515"><time>2026-05-21T13:26:25</time><name>0725</name><cmt>This is the end of the road near the foundation of an old lookout tower. The cache is just a couple hundred yards/meters away.</cmt><desc>End of the road</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=7ed73b88-9876-4348-8994-2c37d5c1da87</url><urlname>End of the road</urlname><sym>Parking Area</sym><type>Waypoint|Parking Area</type></wpt><wpt lat="39.295667" lon="-76.782833"><time>2013-04-07T13:55:46</time><name>TH1FD</name><cmt /><desc>GC1FD Trailhead</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=a3ec8fbe-5d93-42e0-b22a-67ec36b4f7da</url><urlname>GC1FD Trailhead</urlname><sym>Trailhead</sym><type>Waypoint|Trailhead</type></wpt><wpt lat="38.94178333333333" lon="-94.60545"><time>2008-03-21T16:57:44</time><name>PK37</name><cmt>Park here and head down the trail. Take some time to read the history signs.</cmt><desc>Park here for legal access</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/seek/wpt.aspx?WID=f3e9c62a-2c99-4812-9b11-685fda87992b</url><urlname>Park here for legal access</urlname><sym>Parking Area</sym><type>Waypoint|Parking Area</type></wpt><wpt lat="40.91435" lon="-96.387517"><time>2011-07-02T16:48:08</time><name>PK943</name><cmt /><desc>GC943 Parking</desc><u